{"title_page": "Martin Werthmann", "text_new": "'''Martin Werthmann''' (born 1982) is a German artist, who is living and working in Berlin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artfacts.net/artist/martin-werthmann/267807|title=Martin Werthmann {{!}} Artist|last=ArtFacts|website=ArtFacts|language=en|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMartin Werthmann studied from 2004 to 2009 at the [[University of Fine Arts of Hamburg|University of Fine Arts Hamburg]] with [[:de:Andreas Slominski|Andreas Slominski]]. His teachers also included [[Wim Wenders]], [[Fatih Akin]] and [[Daniel Richter (artist)|Daniel Richter]].\n\n== Works ==\nMartin Werthmann mainly comprises large format wood block prints, which consist of several overlapping layers and are printed as unique pieces. The topics often circle around catastrophes, mostly transmitted from found pictures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-martin-werthmann-20160628-snap-htmlstory.html|title=First U.S. show for German woodblock artist is delectably disorienting|last=Ollman|first=Leah|date=2016-06-28|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref> Beside his pictorial works, Werthmann creates large scale installations, like the piece ''Vortex'' from 2014, a water vortex with a diameter of six meters that the observer could enter through the center. In 2019, he created his first scenery for the opera [[Die tote Stadt]] by [[Erich Wolfgang Korngold]], directed by [[:de:Armin Petras|Armin Petras]] and musical direction by [[:de:Yoel Gamzou?fbclid=IwAR2zGyq-mEX4zhKhIbMix6yT QJZu4xxr4MqMcA-G9VAS b46sMihaJ1Lz4|Yoel Gamzou]], which was discussed widely in German newspapers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://taz.de/!5593102/|title=Oper \"Die tote Stadt\" in Bremen: Stadt des toten alten wei\u00dfen Mannes|last=Maier|first=Florian|date=2019-05-19|work=Die Tageszeitung: taz|access-date=2019-08-05|language=de|issn=0931-9085}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/kultur/bremen-tote-stadt-oper-1.4446154|title=\"Die tote Stadt\" in Bremen: Zuckerfee ist ein Mensch|last=Germany|first=S\u00fcddeutsche de GmbH, Munich|website=S\u00fcddeutsche.de|language=de|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions (selection) ==\n\n* 2019 \"Silence after Storm\", Gallery Tore Suessbier, Berlin, Germany (solo)\n* 2018 L\u00f6wenpalais Berlin, Germany (group)\n* 2017 \"D Picture\u201c, Wilding Cran Gallery, Los Angeles, California, USA (group)\n* 2016 \"Martin Werthmann: Anhaltender Regen\", Institut of Modern Art, Nuremberg, Germany (solo)\n* 2016 \"Martin Werthmann:  Connected Bubbles\", Wilding Cran Gallery, Los Angeles, California, USA (solo)\n*2014 \"Sleepless Cheerleaders\", McNamara Art Projects, Hong Kong, China (solo)\n*2012 \"folie \u00e0 deux\", Gallery Etemad, Tehran, Iran (solo)\n*2011 \"Undoubtedly\", Kasseler Kunstverein, Kassel, Germany (group)\n\n== Bibliography ==\nMartin Werthmann: SILENCE, published by Marcus Trauter, Munich, 2019, ISBN 978-3-9819524-5-2\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|url=https://martinwerthmann.de}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=efuT7y-sALc Link to an installation of Martin Werthmann]\n*[http://wildingcran.com/martin-werthmann Website Martin Werthmann at gallery Wilding Cran]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Werthmann, Martin}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Martin Werthmann''' (born 1982) is a German artist, who is living and working in Berlin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artfacts.net/artist/martin-werthmann/267807|title=Martin Werthmann {{!}} Artist|last=ArtFacts|website=ArtFacts|language=en|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMartin Werthmann studied from 2004 to 2009 at the [[University of Fine Arts of Hamburg|University of Fine Arts Hamburg]] with [[:de:Andreas Slominski|Andreas Slominski]]. His teachers also included [[Wim Wenders]], [[Fatih Akin]] and [[Daniel Richter (artist)|Daniel Richter]].\n\n== Works ==\nMartin Werthmann mainly comprises large format wood block prints, which consist of several overlapping layers and are printed as unique pieces. The topics often circle around catastrophes, mostly transmitted from found pictures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-martin-werthmann-20160628-snap-htmlstory.html|title=First U.S. show for German woodblock artist is delectably disorienting|last=Ollman|first=Leah|date=2016-06-28|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref> Beside his pictorial works, Werthmann creates large scale installations, like the piece ''Vortex'' from 2014, a water vortex with a diameter of six meters that the observer could enter through the center. In 2019, he created his first scenery for the opera [[Die tote Stadt]] by [[Erich Wolfgang Korngold]], directed by [[:de:Armin Petras|Armin Petras]] and musical direction by [[:de:Yoel Gamzou?fbclid=IwAR2zGyq-mEX4zhKhIbMix6yT QJZu4xxr4MqMcA-G9VAS b46sMihaJ1Lz4|Yoel Gamzou]], which was discussed widely in German newspapers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://taz.de/!5593102/|title=Oper \"Die tote Stadt\" in Bremen: Stadt des toten alten wei\u00dfen Mannes|last=Maier|first=Florian|date=2019-05-19|work=Die Tageszeitung: taz|access-date=2019-08-05|language=de|issn=0931-9085}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/kultur/bremen-tote-stadt-oper-1.4446154|title=\"Die tote Stadt\" in Bremen: Zuckerfee ist ein Mensch|last=Germany|first=S\u00fcddeutsche de GmbH, Munich|website=S\u00fcddeutsche.de|language=de|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions (selection) ==\n\n* 2019 \"Silence after Storm\", Gallery Tore Suessbier, Berlin, Germany (solo)\n* 2018 L\u00f6wenpalais Berlin, Germany (group)\n* 2017 \"D Picture\u201c, Wilding Cran Gallery, Los Angeles, California, USA (group)\n* 2016 \"Martin Werthmann: Anhaltender Regen\", Institut of Modern Art, Nuremberg, Germany (solo)\n* 2016 \"Martin Werthmann:  Connected Bubbles\", Wilding Cran Gallery, Los Angeles, California, USA (solo)\n*2014 \"Sleepless Cheerleaders\", McNamara Art Projects, Hong Kong, China (solo)\n*2012 \"folie \u00e0 deux\", Gallery Etemad, Tehran, Iran (solo)\n*2011 \"Undoubtedly\", Kasseler Kunstverein, Kassel, Germany (group)\n\n== Bibliography ==\nMartin Werthmann: SILENCE, published by Marcus Trauter, Munich, 2019, ISBN 987-3-9819524-5-2\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|url=https://martinwerthmann.de}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=efuT7y-sALc Link to an installation of Martin Werthmann]\n*[http://wildingcran.com/martin-werthmann Website Martin Werthmann at gallery Wilding Cran]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Werthmann, Martin}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Remline", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix ISBN typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Werthmann"}
{"title_page": "Jill Gohdes", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian field hockey player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox field hockey player\n| name                = Jill Gohdes\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| fullname            = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1990|05|19}}\n| birth_place         = [[Queensland]]\n| height              = \n| position            = Forward\n| currentclub         = \n| clubnumber          = \n| years1              = 2009\u20132015\n| clubs1              = [[Queensland Scorchers|QLD Scorchers]]\n| caps1               = 62\n| goals1              = 11\n| nationalyears1      = 2008\u20132009\n| nationalteam1       = [[Australia women's national under-21 field hockey team|Australia U\u201321]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 14\n| nationalgoals1      = 5\n| nationalyears2      = 2011\n| nationalteam2       = [[Australia women's national field hockey team|Australia]]\n| nationalcaps2       = 10\n| nationalgoals2      = 1\n| medaltemplates      = \n{{MedalSport|Women's [[field hockey]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{AUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Junior Oceania Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2008 Junior Oceania Cup|2008 Brisbane]]|Team}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Australian Youth Olympic Festival]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2009 Australian Youth Olympic Festival|2009 Sydney]]|[[Field hockey at the 2009 Australian Youth Olympic Festival - Women's tournament|Team]]}}\n}}\n'''Jill Gohdes (n\u00e9e Dwyer)''' (born 19 May 1990)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hockey.org.au/ |title=Jillaroos face Japanese senior squad |publisher=[[Hockey Australia]] |website=hockey.org.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> is a former [[field hockey]] player from [[Australia]], who played as a forward.<ref name=\"HOH\">{{cite web |url=https://hockey.org.au/governance/history/history-of-the-hockeyroos/ |title=History of the Hockeyroos |publisher=[[Hockey Australia]] |website=hockey.org.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJill Gohdes is married to fellow former [[Australia women's national field hockey team|Australian]] representative, [[Matthew Gohdes]]. The couple married in December 2015 and have one child.<ref name=\"EASTS\">{{cite web |url=http://quest.smedia.com.au/south-east-advertiser/shared/ShowArticle.aspx?doc=QSEA%2F2019%2F03%2F14&entity=Ar03105&sk=947B7343 |title=Tigers strengthen BHL title hope |publisher=[[Easts Hockey Club]] |website=quest.smedia.com.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-07-27/family-ties-bind-rockhampton-kookaburras-hockey-trio/7665070 |title=Family ties bind Kookaburras players as Rockhampton hockey trio heads to Olympics |publisher=[[ABC News]] |website=abc.net.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Domestic hockey===\n====Club hockey====\nIn her home competition, Division 1 of [[Hockey Queensland]]'s BWHA, Gohdes represents the [[Easts Hockey Club|Easts Tigers]].<ref name=\"EASTS\"/>\n\n====AHL====\nGohdes made her debut in the [[Australian Hockey League]] (AHL) in 2009, as a member of the [[Queensland Scorchers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.clearinghouseforsport.gov.au/Library/archive/digital_archive/hockey |title=Hockey |publisher=[[Government of Australia]] |website=clearinghouseforsport.gov.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Her AHL career spanned seven years, from 2009\u20132015. Throughout this time, she won two AHL titles, in [[2013 Women's Australian Hockey League|2013]] and [[2015 Women's Australian Hockey League|2015]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hockeyaustralia.altiusrt.com/people/935 |title=DWYER Jill |publisher=[[Hockey Australia]] |website=hockeyaustralia.altiusrt.com |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===International hockey===\n====Under\u201321====\nIn 2008, Gohdes made her first appearance for her country as a member of the [[Australia women's national under-21 field hockey team|Australia U\u201321]] side, the Jillaroos, at the [[2008 Junior Oceania Cup|Junior Oceania Cup]] in [[Brisbane, Queensland|Brisbane]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fih.ch/news/hockey-australia-junior-squad-announcements/ |title=Hockey Australia Junior Squad Announcements |publisher=[[International Hockey Federation]] |website=fih.ch |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> At the tournament, Australia won gold, directly qualifying to the [[2009 Women's Hockey Junior World Cup|2009 FIH Junior World Cup]] in [[Boston Massachusetts|Boston]].<ref name=\"2008-09\">{{cite web |url=https://www.clearinghouseforsport.gov.au/Library/archive/digital_archive/hockey/Hockey_Australia_Annual_Report_2008-2009.pdf |title=Hockey Australia Annual Report 2008-2009 |publisher=[[Government of Australia]] |website=clearinghouseforsport.gov.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nGohdes represented the team on two occasions in 2009. Her first tournament was at the [[Field hockey at the 2009 Australian Youth Olympic Festival - Women's tournament|2009 Australian Youth Olympic Festival]] in [[Sydney, New South Wales|Sydney]], winning a silver medal.<ref name=\"2008-09\"/> This was followed by an appearance at the [[Women's FIH Junior World Cup|FIH Junior World Cup]], where the team finished 5th.\n\n====Hockeyroos====\nDespite being a member of the development squad,<ref>{{cite web |title=2011 Women's National Development Squad |url=http://www.hockey.org.au/index.php?id=525 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318134023/http://www.hockey.org.au/index.php?id=525 |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 August 2012 |publisher=[[Hockey Australia]] |website=hockey.org.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Gohdes was called up to make her debut for [[Australia women's national field hockey team|Australia]] in 2011, during a four-nations tournament in [[Rosario, Santa Fe|Rosario]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Dwyer replaces Flanagan in Argentina |url=http://www.hockey.org.au/index.php?id=90&tx_ttnews[tt_news]=531&tx_ttnews[backPid]=88&cHash=0a85858307 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110216071705/http://www.hockey.org.au/index.php?id=90&tx_ttnews[tt_news]=531&tx_ttnews[backPid]=88&cHash=0a85858307 |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 August 2012 |publisher=[[Hockey Australia]] |website=hockey.org.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> She followed this with a string of appearances during test series' in October against [[India women's national field hockey team|India]] and [[China women's national field hockey team|China]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.clearinghouseforsport.gov.au/Library/archive/digital_archive/hockey/Hockey_Australia_Annual_Report_2012_PRINT.pdf |title=Hockey Australia Annual Report 2011-2012 |publisher=[[Government of Australia]] |website=clearinghouseforsport.gov.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe was again named in the development squad in 2012, however did not make any further appearances for the Hockeyroos.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tms.fih.ch/people/22877 |title=DWYER Jill |publisher=[[International Hockey Federation]] |website=tms.fih.ch |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FIH|22877}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gohdes, Jill}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian female field hockey players]]\n[[Category:Female field hockey forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportswomen from Queensland]]\n\n\n{{Australia-fieldhockey-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian field hockey player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox field hockey player\n| name                = Jill Gohdes\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| fullname            = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1990|05|19}}\n| birth_place         = [[Queensland]]\n| height              = \n| position            = Forward\n| currentclub         = \n| clubnumber          = \n| years1              = 2009\u20132015\n| clubs1              = [[Queensland Scorchers|QLD Scorchers]]\n| caps1               = 62\n| goals1              = 11\n| nationalyears1      = 2008\u20132009\n| nationalteam1       = [[Australia women's national under-21 field hockey team|Australia U\u201321]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 14\n| nationalgoals1      = 5\n| nationalyears2      = 2011\n| nationalteam2       = [[Australia women's national field hockey team|Australia]]\n| nationalcaps2       = 10\n| nationalgoals2      = 1\n| medaltemplates      = \n{{MedalSport|Women's [[field hockey]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{AUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Junior Oceania Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2008 Junior Oceania Cup|2008 Brisbane]]|Team}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Australian Youth Olympic Festival]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2009 Australian Youth Olympic Festival|2009 Sydney]]|[[Field hockey at the 2009 Australian Youth Olympic Festival - Women's tournament|Team]]}}\n}}\n'''Jill Gohdes (n\u00e9e Dwyer)''' (born 19 May 1990)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hockey.org.au/ |title=Jillaroos face Japanese senior squad |publisher=[[Hockey Australia]] |website=hockey.org.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> is a former [[field hockey]] player from [[Australia]], who played as a forward.<ref name=\"HOH\">{{cite web |url=https://hockey.org.au/governance/history/history-of-the-hockeyroos/ |title=History of the Hockeyroos |publisher=[[Hockey Australia]] |website=hockey.org.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJill Gohdes is married to fellow former [[Australia women's national field hockey team|Australian]] representative, [[Matthew Gohdes]]. The couple married in December 2015 and have one child.<ref name=\"EASTS\">{{cite web |url=http://quest.smedia.com.au/south-east-advertiser/shared/ShowArticle.aspx?doc=QSEA%2F2019%2F03%2F14&entity=Ar03105&sk=947B7343 |title=Tigers strengthen BHL title hope |publisher=[[Easts Hockey Club]] |website=quest.smedia.com.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-07-27/family-ties-bind-rockhampton-kookaburras-hockey-trio/7665070 |title=Family ties bind Kookaburras players as Rockhampton hockey trio heads to Olympics |publisher=[[ABC News]] |website=abc.net.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Domestic hockey===\n====Club hockey====\nIn her home competition, Division 1 of [[Hockey Queensland]]'s BWHA, Gohdes represents the [[Easts Hockey Club|Easts Tigers]].<ref name=\"EASTS\"/>\n\n====AHL====\nGohdes made her debut in the [[Australian Hockey League]] (AHL) in 2009, as a member of the [[Queensland Scorchers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.clearinghouseforsport.gov.au/Library/archive/digital_archive/hockey |title=Hockey |publisher=[[Government of Australia]] |website=clearinghouseforsport.gov.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Her AHL career spanned seven years, from 2009\u20132015. Throughout this time, she won two AHL titles, in [[2013 Women's Australian Hockey League|2013]] and [[2015 Women's Australian Hockey League|2015]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hockeyaustralia.altiusrt.com/people/935 |title=DWYER Jill |publisher=[[Hockey Australia]] |website=hockeyaustralia.altiusrt.com |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===International hockey===\n====Under\u201321====\nIn 2008, Gohdes made her first appearance for her country as a member of the [[Australia women's national under-21 field hockey team|Australia U\u201321]] side, the Jillaroos, at the [[2008 Junior Oceania Cup|Junior Oceania Cup]] in [[Brisbane, Queensland|Brisbane]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fih.ch/news/hockey-australia-junior-squad-announcements/ |title=Hockey Australia Junior Squad Announcements |publisher=[[International Hockey Federation]] |website=fih.ch |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> At the tournament, Australia won gold, directly qualifying to the [[2009 Women's Hockey Junior World Cup|2009 FIH Junior World Cup]] in [[Boston Massachusetts|Boston]].<ref name=2008-09\">{{cite web |url=https://www.clearinghouseforsport.gov.au/Library/archive/digital_archive/hockey/Hockey_Australia_Annual_Report_2008-2009.pdf |title=Hockey Australia Annual Report 2008-2009 |publisher=[[Government of Australia]] |website=clearinghouseforsport.gov.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nGohdes represented the team on two occasions in 2009. Her first tournament was at the [[Field hockey at the 2009 Australian Youth Olympic Festival - Women's tournament|2009 Australian Youth Olympic Festival]] in [[Sydney, New South Wales|Sydney]], winning a silver medal.<ref name=2008-09\"/> This was followed by an appearance at the [[Women's FIH Junior World Cup|FIH Junior World Cup]], where the team finished 5th.\n\n====Hockeyroos====\nDespite being a member of the development squad,<ref>{{cite web |title=2011 Women's National Development Squad |url=http://www.hockey.org.au/index.php?id=525 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318134023/http://www.hockey.org.au/index.php?id=525 |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 August 2012 |publisher=[[Hockey Australia]] |website=hockey.org.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Gohdes was called up to make her debut for [[Australia women's national field hockey team|Australia]] in 2011, during a four-nations tournament in [[Rosario, Santa Fe|Rosario]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Dwyer replaces Flanagan in Argentina |url=http://www.hockey.org.au/index.php?id=90&tx_ttnews[tt_news]=531&tx_ttnews[backPid]=88&cHash=0a85858307 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110216071705/http://www.hockey.org.au/index.php?id=90&tx_ttnews[tt_news]=531&tx_ttnews[backPid]=88&cHash=0a85858307 |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 August 2012 |publisher=[[Hockey Australia]] |website=hockey.org.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> She followed this with a string of appearances during test series' in October against [[India women's national field hockey team|India]] and [[China women's national field hockey team|China]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.clearinghouseforsport.gov.au/Library/archive/digital_archive/hockey/Hockey_Australia_Annual_Report_2012_PRINT.pdf |title=Hockey Australia Annual Report 2011-2012 |publisher=[[Government of Australia]] |website=clearinghouseforsport.gov.au |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe was again named in the development squad in 2012, however did not make any further appearances for the Hockeyroos.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tms.fih.ch/people/22877 |title=DWYER Jill |publisher=[[International Hockey Federation]] |website=tms.fih.ch |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FIH|22877}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gohdes, Jill}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian female field hockey players]]\n[[Category:Female field hockey forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportswomen from Queensland]]\n\n{{Australia-fieldhockey-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref name fixedWP:REFNAME", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jill_Gohdes"}
{"title_page": "Bomber Crew", "text_new": "{{short description|Video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Bomber Crew\n| developer = Runner Duck\n| publisher = [[Curve Digital]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Linux]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| released = '''Microsoft Windows''', '''OS X''', '''Linux'''{{Video game release|WW| October 19, 2017}}'''PlayStation 4''', '''Xbox One''', '''Nintendo Switch'''{{Video game release|WW| July 10, 2018}}\n| genre = [[Strategy game|Strategy]], [[Real-time strategy]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Bomber Crew''''' is a [[real-time strategy]] video game developed by Runner Duck and published by [[Curve Digital]].<ref>https://www.playstation.com/en-us/games/bomber-crew-ps4/</ref> It was released on Microsoft Windows, OS X and Linux on 19 October 2017.<ref>https://store.steampowered.com/app/537800/Bomber_Crew/</ref> It was released for PlayStation 4, Xbox One and Nintendo Switch on July 10, 2018.<ref>https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Games/Nintendo-Switch-download-software/Bomber-Crew-1400551.html</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe player gives commands to their crew to take them through a campaign of bombing missions set in World War II. New upgrades and equipment become unlocked, and crew members can gain new skills as the game progresses.<ref name=\"NLife\">{{cite web|website=[[Nintendo Life]]|date=July 10, 2018|first=Jon|last=Cousins|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/switch-eshop/bomber_crew|title=Bomber Crew Review (Switch eShop)|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref> The gameplay has been compared to [[FTL: Faster Than Light]].<ref>{{cite web|website=[[Eurogamer]]|date=July 9, 2018|first=Jay|last=Castello|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-07-09-bomber-crew-review-a-chaotic-strategy-game-that-can-be-both-compelling-and-confusing|title=Bomber Crew review - a chaotic strategy game that can be both compelling and confusing|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN\"/> The game features [[permadeath]] on the player's crew.\n\n==Release==\nThere are two packs released as downloadable content: ''Bomber Crew Secret Weapons'', released as on December 15, 2017,<ref name=\"store.steampowered.com\">https://store.steampowered.com/app/754680/Bomber_Crew_Secret_Weapons_DLC/</ref> and ''Bomber Crew: USAAF'', released on October 23, 2018.<ref name=\"store.steampowered.com\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| 4P= 76%<ref name=\"4P\">{{cite web|website=[[4Players]]|date=July 24, 2018|first=Benjamin|last=Schm\u00e4dig|url=https://www.4players.de/4players.php/dispbericht/Allgemein/Test/39055/83288/0/Bomber_Crew.html|title=Test: Bomber Crew (Taktik & Strategie)|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| IGN= 8.5/10<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|first=GB|last=Burford|date=October 26, 2017|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/10/26/bomber-crew-review|title=Bomber Crew Review|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| NLife= 8/10<ref name=\"NLife\"/>\n}}\nThe game received generally favorable or mixed reviews, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/bomber-crew|title=Bomber Crew for Xbox One Reviews|accessdate=2020-01-16|website=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref><ref name=\"MC2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/bomber-crew|title=Bomber Crew for Switch Reviews|accessdate=2020-01-16|website=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref><ref name=\"MC3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/bomber-crew|title=Bomber Crew for PC Reviews|accessdate=2020-01-16|website=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Unity (game engine) games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:2017 video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Bomber Crew\n| developer = Runner Duck\n| publisher = [[Curve Digital]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Linux]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| released = '''Microsoft Windows''', '''OS X''', '''Linux'''{{Video game release|WW| October 19, 2017}}'''PlayStation 4''', '''Xbox One''', '''Nintendo Switch'''{{Video game release|WW| July 10, 2018}}\n| genre = [[Strategy game|Strategy]], [[Real-time strategy]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Bomber Crew''''' is a [[real-time strategy]] video game developed by Runner Duck and published by [[Curve Digital]].<ref>https://www.playstation.com/en-us/games/bomber-crew-ps4/</ref> It was released on Microsoft Windows, OS X and Linux on 19 October, 2017.<ref>https://store.steampowered.com/app/537800/Bomber_Crew/</ref> It was released for Playstation 4, Xbox One and Nintendo Switch on July 10, 2018.<ref>https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Games/Nintendo-Switch-download-software/Bomber-Crew-1400551.html</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe player gives commands to their crew to take them through a campaign of bombing missions set in World War II. New upgrades and equipment become unlocked, and crew members can gain new skills as the game progresses.<ref name=\"NLife\">{{cite web|website=[[Nintendo Life]]|date=July 10, 2018|first=Jon|last=Cousins|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/switch-eshop/bomber_crew|title=Bomber Crew Review (Switch eShop)|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref> The gameplay has been compared to [[FTL: Faster Than Light]].<ref>{{cite web|website=[[Eurogamer]]|date=July 9, 2018|first=Jay|last=Castello|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-07-09-bomber-crew-review-a-chaotic-strategy-game-that-can-be-both-compelling-and-confusing|title=Bomber Crew review - a chaotic strategy game that can be both compelling and confusing|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN\"/> The game features [[permadeath]] on the player's crew.\n\n==Release==\nThere are two packs released as downloadable content: ''Bomber Crew Secret Weapons'', released as on December 15, 2017,<ref>https://store.steampowered.com/app/754680/Bomber_Crew_Secret_Weapons_DLC/</ref> and ''Bomber Crew: USAAF'', released on October 23, 2018.<ref>https://store.steampowered.com/app/754680/Bomber_Crew_Secret_Weapons_DLC/</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| 4P= 76%<ref name=\"4P\">{{cite web|website=[[4Players]]|date=July 24, 2018|first=Benjamin|last=Schm\u00e4dig|url=https://www.4players.de/4players.php/dispbericht/Allgemein/Test/39055/83288/0/Bomber_Crew.html|title=Test: Bomber Crew (Taktik & Strategie)|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| IGN= 8.5/10<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|first=GB|last=Burford|date=October 26, 2017|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/10/26/bomber-crew-review|title=Bomber Crew Review|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| NLife= 8/10<ref name=\"NLife\"/>\n}}\nThe game received generally favorable or mixed reviews, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/bomber-crew|title=Bomber Crew for Xbox One Reviews|accessdate=2020-01-16|website=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref><ref name=\"MC2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/bomber-crew|title=Bomber Crew for Switch Reviews|accessdate=2020-01-16|website=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref><ref name=\"MC3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/bomber-crew|title=Bomber Crew for PC Reviews|accessdate=2020-01-16|website=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how 