{"title_page": "1974\u201375 DDR-Oberliga", "text_new": "{{Other|1974\u201375 Oberliga (disambiguation)}}\n{{infobox football league season\n| competition        = [[DDR-Oberliga]]\n| logo               = \n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| season             = 1974\u201375\n| winners            = [[1. FC Magdeburg]]\n| promoted           = \n| relegated          = {{ubl|[[F.C. Hansa Rostock]]|[[ASG Vorw\u00e4rts Stralsund]]}}\n| continentalcup1    = [[1975\u201376 European Cup|European Cup]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = 1. FC Magdeburg\n| continentalcup2    = [[1975\u201376 European Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]]\n| continentalcup3    = [[1975\u201376 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers = {{ubl|[[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]]|[[Dynamo Dresden]]}}\n| matches            = 182\n| total goals        = 514\n| league topscorer   = [[Manfred Vogel]] (17)<ref>''fuwo'', page: 93</ref>\n| attendance         = 2,209,800<ref name=\"Fuwo\" >''fuwo'', page: 23</ref>\n| average attendance = 12,142<ref name=\"Fuwo\" />\n| prevseason = [[1973\u201374 DDR-Oberliga|1973\u201374]]\n| nextseason = [[1975\u201376 DDR-Oberliga|1975\u201376]]\n}}\nThe '''1974\u201375 DDR-Oberliga''' was the 26th season of the [[DDR-Oberliga]], the first tier of [[East German football league system|league football]] in [[East Germany]].\n\nThe league was contested by fourteen teams. [[1. FC Magdeburg]] won the championship, the club's third and last East German championships.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrchamp.html |title= East Germany - List of Champions |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref name=\"Meister\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/historie/ddr-fussball/meister/ |title= DDR-Meister |date= |website=dfb.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title= East German champions}}</ref>\n\n[[Manfred Vogel]] of [[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]] was the league's top scorer with 17 goals,<ref name=\"Goal\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/torschuetzenkoenige/gdr-oberliga/ |title= DDDR \u00bb Oberliga \u00bb Torsch\u00fctzenk\u00f6nige  |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 25 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=DDR-Oberliga top scorers }}</ref> while [[J\u00fcrgen Pommerenke]] of 1. FC Magdeburg won the seasons [[Footballer of the Year in Germany|East German Footballer of the year]] award.<ref>''fuwo'', page: 92</ref>\n\nOn the strength of the 1974\u201375 title Magdeburg qualified for the [[1975\u201376 European Cup]] where the club was knocked out by [[Malm\u00f6 FF]] in the first round. Seventh-placed club [[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]] qualified for the [[1975\u201376 European Cup Winners' Cup]] as the seasons [[FDGB-Pokal]] winners and was knocked out by [[R.S.C. Anderlecht]] in the semi-finals. Second-placed [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]] qualified for the [[1975\u201376 UEFA Cup]] where it was knocked out in the second round by [[Stal Mielec]] while third-placed [[Dynamo Dresden]] lost to [[Liverpool F.C.]] in the quarter finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec197576.html |title= European Competitions 1975-76 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref>\n\n==Table==\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\nThe 1974\u201375 season saw two newly promoted clubs [[Hallescher FC|Hallescher FC Chemie]] and [[ASG Vorw\u00e4rts Stralsund]].<ref name=\"Ddr\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrhist.html |title= East Germany 1946-1990 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/spielplan/gdr-oberliga-1974-1975-spieltag/26/ |title= DDR \u00bb Oberliga 1974\u201375 |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=DDR-Oberliga 1974\u201375}}</ref>\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=QR\n|sortable_table=y\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=FCM|name_FCM=[[1. FC Magdeburg]]\n|team2=CZJ|name_CZJ=[[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]]\n|team3=DRE|name_DRE=[[Dynamo Dresden]]\n|team4=BER|name_BER=[[Berliner FC Dynamo]]\n|team5=VOR|name_VOR=[[FC Vorw\u00e4rts Frankfurt]]\n|team6=RIE|name_RIE=[[Stahl Riesa|BSG Stahl Riesa]]\n|team7=ZWI|name_ZWI=[[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]]\n|team8=LEI|name_LEI=[[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]]\n|team9=RWE|name_RWE=[[FC Rot-Wei\u00df Erfurt]]\n|team10=KMS|name_KMS=[[Chemnitzer FC|FC Karl-Marx-Stadt]]\n|team11=CHE|name_CHE=[[Hallescher FC|Hallescher FC Chemie]]\n|team12=AUE|name_AUE=[[FC Erzgebirge Aue|BSG Wismut Aue]]\n|team13=ROS|name_ROS=[[F.C. Hansa Rostock]]\n|team14=STR|name_STR=[[ASG Vorw\u00e4rts Stralsund]]\n|win_FCM=17|draw_FCM=7|loss_FCM=2|gf_FCM=57|ga_FCM=28|status_FCM=C\n|win_CZJ=17|draw_CZJ=4|loss_CZJ=5|gf_CZJ=42|ga_CZJ=23\n|win_DRE=12|draw_DRE=8|loss_DRE=6|gf_DRE=42|ga_DRE=30\n|win_BER=10|draw_BER=10|loss_BER=6|gf_BER=47|ga_BER=29\n|win_VOR=8|draw_VOR=10|loss_VOR=8|gf_VOR=37|ga_VOR=31\n|win_RIE=11|draw_RIE=4|loss_RIE=11|gf_RIE=34|ga_RIE=42\n|win_ZWI=9|draw_ZWI=7|loss_ZWI=10|gf_ZWI=42|ga_ZWI=39\n|win_LEI=9|draw_LEI=6|loss_LEI=11|gf_LEI=37|ga_LEI=39\n|win_RWE=9|draw_RWE=5|loss_RWE=12|gf_RWE=37|ga_RWE=42\n|win_KMS=7|draw_KMS=8|loss_KMS=11|gf_KMS=28|ga_KMS=38\n|win_CHE=5|draw_CHE=11|loss_CHE=10|gf_CHE=37|ga_CHE=49\n|win_AUE=7|draw_AUE=7|loss_AUE=12|gf_AUE=24|ga_AUE=43\n|win_ROS=7|draw_ROS=6|loss_ROS=13|gf_ROS=28|ga_ROS=38\n|win_STR=4|draw_STR=7|loss_STR=15|gf_STR=21|ga_STR=46\n\n|status_text_C=1974\u201375 DDR-Oberliga champions\n\n|col_EC=green1|text_EC=Qualified for the [[1975\u201376 European Cup|European Cup]]\n|result1=EC\n|col_UC=blue1|text_UC=Qualified for the [[1975\u201376 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n|result2=UC|result3=UC\n|col_CWC=yellow1|text_CWC=Qualified for the [[1975\u201376 European Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]]\n|result7=CWC\n|col_R=red1|text_R=Relegated to [[DDR-Liga]]\n|result13=R|result14=R\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite magazine |last= |first= |date=1991 |title= Das war unser Fu\u00dfball im Osten|trans-title= This was our football in the East|language=German |magazine= Fu\u00dfball-Woche (fuwo)|location=Berlin |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE|Axel-Springer-Verlag]]}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.f-archiv.de/ Das Deutsche Fussball Archiv] {{in lang|de}} Historic German league tables\n\n{{DDR-Oberliga seasons}}\n{{1974\u201375 in European football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ddr-Oberliga 1974-75}}\n[[Category:DDR-Oberliga seasons|1974-75]]\n[[Category:1974\u201375 in East German football|1]]\n[[Category:1974\u201375 in German football leagues]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other|1974\u201375 Oberliga (disambiguation)}}\n{{infobox football league season\n| competition                = [[DDR-Oberliga]]\n| logo                       =\n| image                      =\n| pixels                     = \n| caption                  = \n| season                     = 1974\u201375\n| winners                    = [[1. FC Magdeburg]]\n| promoted                   = \n| relegated                  = [[F.C. Hansa Rostock]]{{-}}[[ASG Vorw\u00e4rts Stralsund]]\n| continentalcup1            = [[1975\u201376 European Cup|European Cup]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = 1. FC Magdeburg\n| continentalcup2           = [[1975\u201376 European Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers =[[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]]\n| continentalcup3                = [[1975\u201376 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers =[[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]]{{-}}[[Dynamo Dresden]]\n| matches                       = 182\n| total goals                     = 514\n| league topscorer           = [[Manfred Vogel]] (17)<ref>''fuwo'', page: 93</ref>\n| attendance                    = 2,209,800<ref name=\"Fuwo\" >''fuwo'', page: 23</ref>\n| average attendance      = 12,142<ref name=\"Fuwo\" />\n| prevseason                 = [[1973\u201374 DDR-Oberliga|1973\u201374]]\n| nextseason                 = [[1975\u201376 DDR-Oberliga|1975\u201376]]\n}}\nThe '''1974\u201375 DDR-Oberliga''' was the 26th season of the [[DDR-Oberliga]], the first tier of [[East German football league system|league football]] in [[East Germany]].\n\nThe league was contested by fourteen teams. [[1. FC Magdeburg]] won the championship, the club's third and last East German championships.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrchamp.html |title= East Germany - List of Champions |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref name=\"Meister\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/historie/ddr-fussball/meister/ |title= DDR-Meister |date= |website=dfb.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title= East German champions}}</ref>\n\n[[Manfred Vogel]] of [[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]] was the league's top scorer with 17 goals,<ref name=\"Goal\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/torschuetzenkoenige/gdr-oberliga/ |title= DDDR \u00bb Oberliga \u00bb Torsch\u00fctzenk\u00f6nige  |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 25 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=DDR-Oberliga top scorers }}</ref> while [[J\u00fcrgen Pommerenke]] of 1. FC Magdeburg won the seasons [[Footballer of the Year in Germany|East German Footballer of the year]] award.<ref>''fuwo'', page: 92</ref>\n\nOn the strength of the 1974\u201375 title Magdeburg qualified for the [[1975\u201376 European Cup]] where the club was knocked out by [[Malm\u00f6 FF]] in the first round. Seventh-placed club [[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]] qualified for the [[1975\u201376 European Cup Winners' Cup]] as the seasons [[FDGB-Pokal]] winners and was knocked out by [[R.S.C. Anderlecht]] in the semi-finals. Second-placed [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]] qualified for the [[1975\u201376 UEFA Cup]] where it was knocked out in the second round by [[Stal Mielec]] while third-placed [[Dynamo Dresden]] lost to [[Liverpool F.C.]] in the quarter finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec197576.html |title= European Competitions 1975-76 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref>\n\n==Table==\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\nThe 1974\u201375 season saw two newly promoted clubs [[Hallescher FC|Hallescher FC Chemie]] and [[ASG Vorw\u00e4rts Stralsund]].<ref name=\"Ddr\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrhist.html |title= East Germany 1946-1990 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/spielplan/gdr-oberliga-1974-1975-spieltag/26/ |title= DDR \u00bb Oberliga 1974\u201375 |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=DDR-Oberliga 1974\u201375}}</ref>\n{{fb cl header|sort=y|noqr=y|winpoints=2}}\n|-bgcolor=\"90EE90\"\n|1||align=\"left\"|[[1. FC Magdeburg]] (C)||26||17||{{0}}7||{{0}}2||57||28||+29||'''41-11'''\n|-bgcolor=\"97DEFF\"\n|2||align=\"left\"|[[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]]||26||17||{{0}}4||{{0}}5||42||23||+19||'''38-14'''\n|-bgcolor=\"97DEFF\"\n|3||align=\"left\"|[[Dynamo Dresden]]||26||12||{{0}}8||{{0}}6||42||30||+12||'''32-20'''\n|-\n|4||align=\"left\"|[[Berliner FC Dynamo]]||26||10||10||{{0}}6||47||29||+18||'''30-22'''\n|-\n|5||align=\"left\"|[[FC Vorw\u00e4rts Frankfurt]]||26||{{0}}8||10||{{0}}8||37||31||+6||'''26-26'''\n|-\n|6||align=\"left\"|[[Stahl Riesa|BSG Stahl Riesa]]||26||11||{{0}}4||11||34||42||&minus;8||'''26-26'''\n|-bgcolor=\"ccffff\"\n|7||align=\"left\"|[[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]]||26||{{0}}9||{{0}}7||10||42||39||+3||'''25-27'''\n|-\n|8||align=\"left\"|[[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]]||26||{{0}}9||{{0}}6||11||37||39||&minus;2||'''24-28'''\n|-\n|9||align=\"left\"|[[FC Rot-Wei\u00df Erfurt]]||26||{{0}}9||{{0}}5||12||37||42||&minus;5||'''23-29'''\n|-\n|10||align=\"left\"|[[Chemnitzer FC|FC Karl-Marx-Stadt]]||26||{{0}}7||{{0}}8||11||28||38||&minus;10||'''22-30'''\n|-\n|11||align=\"left\"|[[Hallescher FC|Hallescher FC Chemie]]||26||{{0}}5||11||10||37||49||&minus;12||'''21-31'''\n|-\n|12||align=\"left\"|[[FC Erzgebirge Aue|BSG Wismut Aue]]||26||{{0}}7||{{0}}7||12||24||43||&minus;19||'''21-31'''\n|-bgcolor=\"FFCCCC\"\n|13||align=\"left\"|[[F.C. Hansa Rostock]]||26||{{0}}7||{{0}}6||13||28||38||&minus;10||'''20-32'''\n|-bgcolor=\"FFCCCC\"\n|14||align=\"left\"|[[ASG Vorw\u00e4rts Stralsund]]||26||{{0}}4||{{0}}7||15||21||46||&minus;25||'''15-37'''\n|}\n\n{| bgcolor=\"#f7f8ff\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" style=\"font-size: 95%; border: gray solid 1px; border-collapse: collapse;text-align:center;\"\n|-\n| style=\"background: \"#ffffff\" width=\"20\" | (C)\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" align=\"left\" | 1974\u201375 DDR-Oberliga champions\n|-\n| style=\"background:#90EE90;\" width=\"20\" | \n| bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" align=\"left\" | Qualified for the [[1975\u201376 European Cup|European Cup]]\n|-\n| style=\"background: #97DEFF;\" width=\"20\" | \n| bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" align=\"left\" | Qualified for the [[1975\u201376 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n|-\n| style=\"background: #ccffff;\" width=\"20\" | \n| bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" align=\"left\" | Qualified for the [[1975\u201376 European Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]]\n|-\n| style=\"background: #FFCCCC\" width=\"20\" | \n| bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" align=\"left\" | Relegated to [[DDR-Liga]]\n|}\n\n<small>'''Pld''' = Matches played; '''W''' = Matches won; '''D''' = Matches drawn; '''L''' = Matches lost; '''GF''' = Goals for; '''GA''' = Goals against; '''GD''' = Goal difference; '''Pts''' = Points</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite magazine |last= |first= |date=1991 |title= Das war unser Fu\u00dfball im Osten|trans-title= This was our football in the East|language=German |magazine= Fu\u00dfball-Woche (fuwo)|location=Berlin |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE|Axel-Springer-Verlag]]}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.f-archiv.de/ Das Deutsche Fussball Archiv] {{in lang|de}} Historic German league tables\n\n{{DDR-Oberliga seasons}}\n{{1974\u201375 in European football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ddr-Oberliga 1974-75}}\n[[Category:DDR-Oberliga seasons|1974-75]]\n[[Category:1974\u201375 in East German football|1]]\n[[Category:1974\u201375 in German football leagues]]\n", "name_user": "Frietjes", "label": "safe", "comment": "expand templates perFb team TfD outcomeandFb competition TfD outcomeandFb cl TfD outcomeandFb rbr TfD outcome", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1974%E2%80%9375_DDR-Oberliga"}
{"title_page": "Super Smash Bros. Ultimate", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 fighting game}}\n{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title      = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate\n| image      = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate.jpg\n| caption    = Cover art, showcasing the game's large playable roster{{efn|[[Yoshi]] (bottom-left) is excluded in German copies because of a [[USK]] label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/06/random_yoshi_gets_cut_from_the_german_box_art_for_super_smash_bros_ultimate|title=Random: Yoshi Gets Cut From The German Box Art For Super Smash Bros. Ultimate|last=Reseigh-Lincoln|first=Dom|date=June 22, 2018|website=Nintendo Life|accessdate=December 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221403/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/06/random_yoshi_gets_cut_from_the_german_box_art_for_super_smash_bros_ultimate|archive-date=September 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n| developer  = {{ubl|[[Bandai Namco Studios]]|[[Sora Ltd.]]}}\n| publisher  = [[Nintendo]]\n| director   = [[Masahiro Sakurai]]\n| producer   = {{ubl|Shinya Saito|Yoshito Higuchi}}\n| composer   = [[Hideki Sakamoto]]<!--Most of the original music is based around Hideki Sakamoto's main theme \"Lifelight\"-->\n| artist     = Yusuke Nakano\n| programmer = Tetsuya Otaguro\n| designer   = <!--Wikidata-->\n| series     = ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]''\n| platforms  = [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released   = December 7, 2018\n| genre      = [[Fighting game|Fighting]]\n| modes      = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'''''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|'''''Super Smash Bros. Special'''''|\u5927\u4e71\u95d8\u30b9\u30de\u30c3\u30b7\u30e5\u30d6\u30e9\u30b6\u30fc\u30ba {{ruby|SPECIAL|\u30b9\u30da\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb}}|Dai rant\u014d Sumasshu Buraz\u0101zu Supesharu|lead=yes}}}} is a 2018 [[gaming crossover|crossover]] [[fighting game]] developed by [[Bandai Namco Studios]] and [[Sora Ltd.]] and published by [[Nintendo]] for the [[Nintendo Switch]]. It is the fifth installment in the ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' series, succeeding [[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U|''Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS'' and ''Wii U'']]. The game follows the series' traditional style of gameplay: controlling one of the [[Characters in the Super Smash Bros. series|various characters]], players must use differing attacks to weaken their opponents and knock them out of an arena. It features a wide variety of [[game modes]], including a [[Campaign (role-playing games)|campaign]] for [[single-player]] and [[multiplayer]] versus modes. ''Ultimate'' features over 80 playable fighters, including everyone from all previous ''Super Smash Bros.'' games, alongside several newcomers. The roster ranges from Nintendo mascots to characters from [[Third party developer|third-party]] franchises, with the game being supported with post-release [[downloadable content]] that adds more.\n\nPlanning for the game had begun by December 2015, with full development starting after the completion of ''3DS''/''Wii U''{{'s}} [[downloadable content]] (DLC). Series creator and director [[Masahiro Sakurai]] returned along with Bandai Namco Studios and Sora, the studios that developed ''3DS''/''Wii U,'' with the return of the studios speeding up the preparation process. Sakurai's goal with ''Ultimate'' was to include every character from previous games despite the various development and licensing problems this would cause. Several well-known video game musicians contributed to the soundtrack, with [[Hideki Sakamoto]] writing the main theme \"Lifelight\".\n\nNintendo teased ''Ultimate'' in a [[Nintendo Direct]] in March 2018 and fully revealed it at [[E3 2018]] the following June. It later received two additional dedicated Nintendo Directs before releasing on December 7, 2018. The game received universal acclaim, with some critics calling it the best of the series. They praised its amount of content and fine-tuning of existing ''Smash'' gameplay elements, although its online mode received some criticism. By December 2019, the game had sold over 17.68 million copies worldwide, making it the best-selling fighting game of all time.\n\n==Gameplay==\n{{Main|Super Smash Bros.#Gameplay|l1=Gameplay of Super Smash Bros.}}\n[[File:Super Smash Bros. Ultimate gameplay.jpg|thumb|A four-player match on the Great Plateau stage (from ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]]'') between [[Ganondorf]], [[Link (The Legend of Zelda)|Link]], [[Mario]] and [[Mega Man (character)|Mega Man]]|alt=|left]]''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'' is a [[fighting game]] for up to eight players in which characters from [[Nintendo]] games and other third-party franchises must try to knock each other out of an arena. Each player has a percentage meter which raises when they take damage, making them easier to launch in the air and out of the arena.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/e3-2018-get-your-first-look-at-super-smash-bros-ultimate |title=E3 2018: Get your first look at Super Smash Bros. Ultimate |date=June 12, 2018 |website=[[CNET]] |access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> Standard battles use one of three victory conditions: Timed, where players aim to win the most points by defeating opponents within a time limit; Stock, where players have a set number of lives and must aim to be the last player standing; and Stamina, where players must simply reduce their opponent's health down to zero to defeat them. Players can adjust the rules to their liking and save them as presets for future matches.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.newsweek.com/super-smash-bros-ultimate-simon-belmont-king-k-rool-echo-fighters-chrom-dark-1063761 | title = Simon Belmont, King K. Rool And More Details From \u2018Super Smash Bros. Ultimate\u2019 Direct | first = Philip | last = Martinez | date = August 8, 2018 | accessdate = August 8, 2018 | work = [[Newsweek]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180808174026/https://www.newsweek.com/super-smash-bros-ultimate-simon-belmont-king-k-rool-echo-fighters-chrom-dark-1063761 | archive-date = August 8, 2018 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPlayers can use various items to attack enemies or grant them power-ups, along with Pok\u00e9 Balls and Assist Trophies which respectively summon [[Pok\u00e9mon]] and other non-playable characters to assist them in battle. In Timed matches, certain Assist Trophies can be attacked and defeated to earn points.<ref name=\"every character\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/12/17451586/super-smash-bros-ultimate-nintendo-switch-characters-release-date-e3 |title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate will feature every single character from the series\u2019 history |work=The Verge |access-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614040807/https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/12/17451586/super-smash-bros-ultimate-nintendo-switch-characters-release-date-e3 |archivedate=June 14, 2018  }}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/12/17452068/super-smash-bros-ultimate-fighters-roster-nintendo-switch |title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate brings back every Smash fighter ever |work=Polygon |access-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614224736/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/12/17452068/super-smash-bros-ultimate-fighters-roster-nintendo-switch |archivedate=June 14, 2018  }}</ref><ref name=\"usgamer engine\" /> Each character also possesses a powerful Final Smash attack, which can be performed either by obtaining a Smash Ball or by filling up a special meter, both of which can be toggled on and off.<ref name=\"every character\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"usgamer engine\" /> The game features 103 different stages included in the base game, with additional ones coming packaged with DLC fighters. They can all be played in alternative Battlefield and Omega forms or can be toggled to remove stage hazards. A new feature called Stage Morph allows players to select two stages that the game alternates between at certain intervals during a match.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/12/17453434/super-smash-bros-ultimate-ridley-playable-character-metroid-nintendo-switch |title=Metroid\u2019s Ridley will be playable in Super Smash Bros. Ultimate |last=Gilliam |first=Ryan |date=June 12, 2018 |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612210708/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/12/17453434/super-smash-bros-ultimate-ridley-playable-character-metroid-nintendo-switch |archivedate=June 12, 2018  }}</ref><ref name=\"shacknews everything\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/super-smash-bros-ultimate-nintendo-e3-2018-direct-973208|title=New details for \u2018Super Smash Bros.\u2019 on Switch were revealed at E3 2018|date=June 12, 2018|work=Newsweek|access-date=June 12, 2018|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612192221/http://www.newsweek.com/super-smash-bros-ultimate-nintendo-e3-2018-direct-973208|archivedate=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"polygon 100stages\">{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/8/8/17663912/super-smash-bros-ultimate-stages-new-donk-city-stage-morph | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate will include 103 stages, stage morph feature | first = Ben | last = Kuchera | date = August 8, 2018 | accessdate = August 8, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180808182619/https://www.polygon.com/2018/8/8/17663912/super-smash-bros-ultimate-stages-new-donk-city-stage-morph | archive-date = August 8, 2018 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Other tweaks include new icons and gauges for character-specific abilities, such as [[Cloud Strife|Cloud]]'s Limit gauge.<ref name=\"shacknews everything\" />\n\nIn addition to returning modes such as Classic, Special Smash, and Home-Run Contest, new modes are added to the game include Smashdown, where each character can only be played once, Squad Strike, where players battle in teams of multiple characters, and a tournament mode that allows up to 32 players to battle in playoff brackets.<ref name=\"polygon new modes\">{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/8/8/17664076/super-smash-bros-ultimate-new-gameplay-modes-nintendo-switch | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate features some new gameplay modes | first = Petrana | last = Radulovic | date = August 8, 2018 | accessdate = August 8, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180809025614/https://www.polygon.com/2018/8/8/17664076/super-smash-bros-ultimate-new-gameplay-modes-nintendo-switch | archive-date = August 9, 2018 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/06/12/e3-2018-super-smash-bros-ultimate-switch |title=E3 2018: Super Smash Bros. Ultimate roster includes every character from previous games \u2013 out December 7 |last=Nunneley |first=Stepheney |date=June 12, 2018 |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |website=[[VG247]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614003835/https://www.vg247.com/2018/06/12/e3-2018-super-smash-bros-ultimate-switch/ |archivedate=June 14, 2018  }}</ref>\n\n=== Spirits ===\n[[File:Smash Ultimate spirit.jpg|thumb|A typical spirit battle, here players must face off against an [[Incineroar]] meant to represent [[Tom Nook]] from the [[Animal Crossing|''Animal Crossing'' series]]]]\nAnother set of modes revolves around a new mechanic known as spirits, which replaces the collectible trophies from previous games. Each of these spirits, based on a crossover character, can be used to power up a fighter with unique abilities, which can be used to fight against human or computer opponents and earn new spirits.<ref name=\"polygon spirits mode\" /> Players gain spirits through pre-made challenges known as \"Spirit Battles\" that capture the theme of the character depicted by the spirit, embodied by one or more of the game's fighters and other specific level effects; for example, the spirit battle of Rayquaza, a flying dragon Pok\u00e9mon, requires players to defeat a large version of Ridley with added wind effects. A separate Spirit Board mode presents a rotating set of spirit battles for players to gain spirits from. Spirits have a growth and evolution system similar to Pok\u00e9mon games, leveling the Spirits to gain more powerful effects or means of merging core abilities into a new Spirit.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/19/18096276/super-smash-bros-ultimate-single-player-mode-switch-hands-on | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate\u2019s single-player mode shines on the Switch | first = Chaim | last = Gartenburg | date = November 19, 2018 | accessdate = November 19, 2018 | work = [[The Verge]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181120055140/https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/19/18096276/super-smash-bros-ultimate-single-player-mode-switch-hands-on | archive-date = November 20, 2018 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Nintendo offers limited-timed Spirit events in cross-promotion with other games and franchises, where a number of them are only available to collect during the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://in.ign.com/super-smash-bros-for-nintendo-switch/139840/news/daemon-x-machina-spirit-event-coming-to-super-smash-bros-ultimate|title=Daemon X Machina Spirit Event Coming To Super Smash Bros. Ultimate|date=2019-09-26|website=IGN India|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n==== World of Light ====\nThe spirit mechanic is prominent in the game's single-player adventure mode, ''World of Light''.<ref name=\"polygon spirits mode\">{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/1/18051614/super-smash-bros-ultimate-spirits-mode-characters | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate\u2019s Spirits Mode adds tons more characters to the game | first = Allegra | last = Frank | date = November 1, 2018 | accessdate = November 1, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181101151524/https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/1/18051614/super-smash-bros-ultimate-spirits-mode-characters | archive-date = November 1, 2018 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.destructoid.com/super-smash-bros-ultimate-has-a-new-world-of-light-adventure-mode-subspace-emissary-will-not-return-529433.phtml | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate has a new 'World of Light' adventure mode, SubSpace Emissary will not return | first = Chris | last = Carter | date = November 1, 2018 | accessdate = November 1, 2018 | work = [[Destructoid]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181101151336/https://www.destructoid.com/super-smash-bros-ultimate-has-a-new-world-of-light-adventure-mode-subspace-emissary-will-not-return-529433.phtml | archive-date = November 1, 2018 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The mode's narrative begins with an evil entity, Galeem, destroying the ''Smash Bros.'' world, vaporizing nearly all of the fighter characters and placing them under his imprisonment; only [[Kirby (character)|Kirby]], due to his Warp Star, evades this attack.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.destructoid.com/super-smash-bros-director-says-there-s-a-practical-reason-why-kirby-survived-the-apocalypse-in-the-last-trailer-533204.phtml | title = Super Smash Bros. director says there's a practical reason why Kirby survived the apocalypse in the last trailer | first = Chris | last = Carter | date = December 2, 2018 | accessdate = December 6, 2018 | work = [[Destructoid]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190409121331/https://www.destructoid.com/super-smash-bros-director-says-there-s-a-practical-reason-why-kirby-survived-the-apocalypse-in-the-last-trailer-533204.phtml | archive-date = April 9, 2019 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The Player must explore the ruined world to rescue captured fighters and spirits by completing marked challenges. Players can use regained allies and spirits to overcome certain challenges on the map and eventually defeat Galeem.<ref name=\"polygon spirits mode\"/><ref name=\"ignrev\"/> However, after Galeem is defeated, a new enemy, Dharkon takes over and, after being defeated, wages war against Galeem, and players must destroy both of them. If just Galeem is defeated, Dharkon will engulf the world in darkness, but if just Dharkon is defeated, then Galeem will cover the universe with light. However, there is a path that allows players to defeat both of them at once. When done so, the spirits are freed from the deities' control and return to the real world.\n\n=== Multiplayer ===\nThe game supports local multiplayer, local wireless with other systems, and online play via Wi-Fi or LAN connections. By defeating players online, players can earn tags which can be traded for in-game currency to buy new spirits, music, and [[Mii]] Fighter costumes. The game is compatible with Joy-Con controllers, the Nintendo Switch Pro Controller, and [[GameCube controller]]s via the use of a USB adaptor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/12/17451554/super-smash-bros-ultimate-gamecube-controller-support-e3-2018|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate will support GameCube controllers|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=|website=The Verge|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614150834/https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/12/17451554/super-smash-bros-ultimate-gamecube-controller-support-e3-2018|archive-date=June 14, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref> Like in the previous entry, [[amiibo]] figurines can be used to create AI-controlled Figure Players that can be trained to become stronger.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/12/17453568/super-smash-bros-ultimate-gamecube-controller-support |title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate will support GameCube controllers, amiibo |first=Michael |last=McWhertor |date=June 12, 2018 |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612210536/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/12/17453568/super-smash-bros-ultimate-gamecube-controller-support |archivedate=June 12, 2018  }}</ref><ref name=\"IGN cite new Amiibo SSBU\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/06/12/e3-2018-super-smash-bros-ultimate-ridley-inkling-amiibo-announced |title=E3 2018: Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Ridley, Inkling Amiibo Announced |first=Alex |last=Osborn |date=June 12, 2018 |accessdate=June 14, 2018 |work=[[IGN]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615011049/http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/06/12/e3-2018-super-smash-bros-ultimate-ridley-inkling-amiibo-announced |archivedate=June 15, 2018  }}</ref> Sometime after the game's release, a service for the Nintendo Switch Online mobile app, known as \"Smash World,\" was launched, which allows players to check their game statistics in addition to sharing images and videos captured from the game to social media.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/1/18051500/super-smash-bros-ultimate-world-nintendo-switch | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate is getting its own dedicated video sharing service | first = Andrew | last = Webster | date = November 1, 2018 | accessdate = November 1, 2018 | work = [[The Verge]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181102175631/https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/1/18051500/super-smash-bros-ultimate-world-nintendo-switch | archive-date = November 2, 2018 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''Ultimate'' features over 900 music tracks, which can be played through the Switch's handheld mode while in standby mode.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimate-soundtrack-has-over-800-/1100-6461025/ | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Soundtrack Has Over 800 Songs | first = Tamoor | last = Hussain | date = August 8, 2018 | accessdate = August 8, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180808182144/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimate-soundtrack-has-over-800-/1100-6461025/ | archive-date = August 8, 2018 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Version 3.0 of the game, released in April 2019, adds a Stage Builder allowing players to create their own custom stages, and which they can share or download through the Switch Online service. The update also includes a replay editor that allow players to edit stored replays and share those with others or download to other devices. These will be also available within the Smash World app.<ref name=\"gspot v3.0\">{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/smash-bros-ultimate-30-update-adds-stage-builder-v/1100-6466312/ | title = Smash Bros. Ultimate 3.0 Update Adds Stage-Builder, Video Editor, Persona 5 Character, More | first = Eddie | last = Makuch | date = April 16, 2019 | accessdate = April 16, 2019 | work = [[GameSpot]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190417015135/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/smash-bros-ultimate-30-update-adds-stage-builder-v/1100-6466312/ | archive-date = April 17, 2019 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> An update in May 2019 provided limited support for the [[virtual reality]] VR Kit of [[Nintendo Labo]], allowing a player to view computer-only matches in VR or playing in a 1-on-1 mode against the computer.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/super-smash-bros-uitimate-now-has-virtual-reality-supp-1835137993 | title = Super Smash Bros. UItimate Now Has Virtual Reality Support | first=  Luke | last = Plunkett | date = May 30, 2019 | accessdate = May 30, 2019  |work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref>\n\n===Playable characters===\n{{See also|Characters in the Super Smash Bros. series}}\n''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'', as with other games in the ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' series, features a [[Crossover (video games)|crossover]] cast of fighters from several different [[Nintendo franchises]], as well as fighters from series by [[Third-party developer|third-party]] developers such as [[Konami]], [[Sega]], [[Capcom]], [[Bandai Namco Entertainment]], [[Square Enix]], [[PlatinumGames]], [[Atlus]], [[Microsoft]], and [[SNK]]. The base game features 74 playable fighters,{{efn|Pok\u00e9mon Trainer, who uses three summonable Pok\u00e9mon, is regarded as a single character; the total number of fighters goes to 76 if one counts each of their Pok\u00e9mon individually.}} consisting of all 63 previous fighters from past entries and 11 new ones: the Inklings from ''[[Splatoon]]''; [[Princess Daisy]] from the ''[[Mario (franchise)|Mario]]'' series; [[Ridley (Metroid)|Ridley]] and [[Dark Samus]] from the ''[[Metroid]]'' series; [[Simon Belmont|Simon]] and [[Richter Belmont]] from the ''[[Castlevania]]'' series; Chrom from ''[[Fire Emblem Awakening]]''; [[King K. Rool]] from the ''[[Donkey Kong]]'' series; [[Isabelle (Animal Crossing)|Isabelle]] from the ''[[Animal Crossing]]'' series; [[Ken Masters]] from the ''[[Street Fighter]]'' series; and [[Incineroar]] from [[Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon|''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'']].<ref name=\"VG247\">{{cite web |last1=Donaldson |first1=Alex |title=Smash Bros Ultimate character roster: all fighters, stages and DLC for Smash on Switch |url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/11/28/smash-bros-ultimate-character-roster-all-characters-stages-unlockables-dlc/ |website=[[VG247]] |accessdate=December 22, 2018 |date=November 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222174412/https://www.vg247.com/2018/11/28/smash-bros-ultimate-character-roster-all-characters-stages-unlockables-dlc/ |archive-date=December 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> When starting the game, players only have access to the eight starter characters of the original 1999 ''[[Super Smash Bros. (video game)|Super Smash Bros.]]'' game and must unlock the rest by completing the game's Classic mode, playing through World of Light, or fighting a certain amount of battles.<ref name=\"polygon roster\">{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/12/17452068/super-smash-bros-ultimate-fighters-roster-nintendo-switch |title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate brings back every Smash fighter ever |first=Allegra |last=Frank |date=June 12, 2018 |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614224736/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/12/17452068/super-smash-bros-ultimate-fighters-roster-nintendo-switch |archivedate=June 14, 2018  }}</ref>{{citation needed |reason=The source doesn't state that only the first eight characters are unlocked from the start and that other can be unlocked by playing through World of Light or completing a certain amount of battles |date=March 2020}}\n\nCertain characters whose movesets are directly based on other characters in the game are now classified as \"Echo Fighters\", possessing similar movesets and proportions to the fighters they are based on, but with their own unique animations and gameplay differences. On the character selection screen, these characters can either be listed individually or stacked with the fighters they are based on.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimate-gets-chrom-and-dark-samu/1100-6461022/ | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Gets Chrom And Dark Samus As Echo Fighters, Here's How They Work | first = Kevin | last = Knezevic | date = August 8, 2018 | accessdate = August 8, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref><ref name=\"Kotaku\" /> Select characters also have alternative skins featuring different genders or sometimes other characters, such as [[Bowser Jr.]] who has a selectable appearance to be any of the other [[Koopalings]] but otherwise have identical animations and abilities.<ref name=\"shacknews everything\" /><ref name=\"verge sakurai\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/12/17453214/super-smash-bros-ultimate-nintendo-switch-masahiro-sakurai-e3 |title=Why Super Smash Bros. Ultimate was such a daunting game for its creators to build |first=Andrew |last=Webster |date=June 12, 2018 |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |website=[[The Verge]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612211115/https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/12/17453214/super-smash-bros-ultimate-nintendo-switch-masahiro-sakurai-e3 |archivedate=June 12, 2018  }}</ref><ref name=\"Kotaku\">{{cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/everything-we-know-about-super-smash-bros-ultimate-1826763007 |title=Everything We Know About Super Smash Bros. Ultimate |first=Cecilia |last=D'Anastasio |date=June 12, 2018 |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |work=[[Kotaku]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612170503/https://kotaku.com/everything-we-know-about-super-smash-bros-ultimate-1826763007 |archivedate=June 12, 2018}}</ref> Several returning characters received updates to their outfits, such as [[Mario]] having Cappy from ''[[Super Mario Odyssey]]'' accompanying him and [[Link (The Legend of Zelda)|Link]] wearing his outfit from ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]]''.<ref name=\"verge sakurai\" />\n\nAdditional fighters have been added to the game via post-release [[downloadable content]] (DLC). The first of these, Piranha Plant from the ''Mario'' series, was released in January 2019 and made available for free to those who purchased and registered the game with a [[My Nintendo]] account before the end of that month.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usgamer.net/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimate-piranha-plant-dlc-nintendo-playable-now | title = Piranha Plant is Now Playable in Super Smash Bros. Ultimate | first = Matt | last = Kim | date = January 29, 2019 | accessdate = January 29, 2019 | work = [[USGamer]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190130110249/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimate-piranha-plant-dlc-nintendo-playable-now | archive-date = January 30, 2019 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kotaku.co.uk/2018/11/05/piranha-plant-coming-to-smash-ultimate-around-february-not-part-of-fighters-pass|title=Piranha Plant Coming to Smash Ultimate Around February, Not Part of Fighters Pass|website=Kotaku UK|accessdate=December 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105203059/http://www.kotaku.co.uk/2018/11/05/piranha-plant-coming-to-smash-ultimate-around-february-not-part-of-fighters-pass|archive-date=November 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Additional fighters, each coming with a unique stage and related music, have been released both individually and as part of Fighters Pass bundles.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/1/18051896/super-smash-bros-ultimate-dlc-characters-price-release-date | title = Super Smash Bros. DLC will add 5 characters to the roster | first = Matt | last = Patches | date = November 1, 2018 | accessdate = November 1, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181101200302/https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/1/18051896/super-smash-bros-ultimate-dlc-characters-price-release-date | archive-date = November 1, 2018 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kotaku.co.uk/2018/11/01/heres-our-thoughts-on-everything-that-happened-during-the-smash-bros-ultimate-direct|title=Here's Our Thoughts on Everything That Happened During The Smash Bros. Ultimate Direct|website=Kotaku UK|accessdate=December 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104211331/http://www.kotaku.co.uk/2018/11/01/heres-our-thoughts-on-everything-that-happened-during-the-smash-bros-ultimate-direct|archive-date=November 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The first Fighters Pass consisted of five characters: [[Joker (Persona)|Joker]] from [[Atlus]]' role-playing game ''[[Persona 5]]'', released in April 2019;<ref name=\"gspot v3.0\"/> the Hero{{efn|Despite the name referring to a single character, the Hero represents four different protagonists from the ''Dragon Quest'' series. His default appearance is the Luminary/Eleven from ''[[Dragon Quest XI]]'', with [[Erdrick]]/Arusu from ''[[Dragon Quest III]]'',  Solo from ''[[Dragon Quest IV]]'', and Eight from ''[[Dragon Quest VIII]]'' appearing as alternate costumes.}} from Square Enix's ''[[Dragon Quest]]'' series, released in July 2019;<ref>{{cite web |last1=McWhertor |first1=Michael |title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate\u2019s new Dragon Quest fighter arrives Tuesday |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/7/30/20746870/super-smash-bros-ultimate-dragon-quest-character-dlc-release-date-gameplay |website=Polygon |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> Banjo and Kazooie from [[Rare (company)|Rare]]'s ''[[Banjo-Kazooie (series)|Banjo-Kazooie]]'' series, released in September 2019;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/09/04/banjo-kazooie-enter-super-smash-bros-ultimate-today/|title=Banjo-Kazooie enter Super Smash Bros. Ultimate today|date=September 4, 2019|website=VentureBeat|access-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref> [[Terry Bogard]] from [[SNK]]'s ''[[Fatal Fury]]'' series, released in November 2019;<ref name=\"kotaku terry\">{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/super-smash-bros-ultimate-s-latest-dlc-fighter-goes-li-1839662096 | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate\u2019s Latest Fighter, Terry, Goes Live Today | first=Mike | last = Fahey | date = November 6, 2019 | accessdate = November 6, 2019 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref> and Byleth from ''[[Fire Emblem: Three Houses]]'', released in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://venturebeat.com/2020/01/16/byleth-from-fire-emblem-three-houses-is-super-smash-bros-ultimates-next-fighter/ | title=  Byleth from Fire Emblem: Three Houses is Super Smash Bros. Ultimate\u2019s next fighter | first = Mike | last = Minotti | date = January 16, 2020 | accessdate = January 16, 2020 | work = [[Venture Beat]] }}</ref> \n\nWhile Nintendo had originally planned to limit new fighters to those in the initial Fighters Pass, the company announced plans in September 2019 to release additional DLC fighters via Fighters Pass Volume 2, which includes six additional fighters that are scheduled to be released in 2020\u20132021.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://venturebeat.com/2020/01/16/super-smash-bros-ultimate-is-still-getting-six-more-new-fighters/ | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate is still getting six more new fighters | first = Mike | last = Minotti | date = January 16, 2020 | accessdate = January 16, 2020 | work = [[VentureBeat]] }}</ref> Sakurai stated in February 2020 that there are no further plans for any additional Fighters Passes after the second one for ''Ultimate''. Once the second Fighters Pass is complete, it is expected to bring the total fighter roster to 88.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-02-19-super-smash-bros-ultimates-second-fighter-pass-is-its-last | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate's second fighter pass is its last | first= Tom | last = Phillips | date = February 19, 2020 | accessdate = February 19, 2020 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> In March 2020, a character from ''[[Arms (video game)|Arms]]'' was announced as the first DLC of Fighters Pass Vol. 2, with a tentative release date of June 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimates-next-dlc-fighter-is-fro/1100-6475254/ | title=  Super Smash Bros. Ultimate's Next DLC Fighter Is From Arms | first = Kevin | last = Knezevic | date = March 26, 2020 | accessdate = March 26, 2020 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'' was developed by [[Bandai Namco Studios]] and [[Sora Ltd.]], the same studios that developed [[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U|''Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS'' and ''Wii U'']], for the [[Nintendo Switch]], with series creator [[Masahiro Sakurai]] returning as game director.<ref name=\"verge sakurai\" /> Unlike previous ''Super Smash Bros.'' games, the team was not assembled from the ground up, which sped up preparation time.<ref name=\"SiSP2\"/> The project plan for the game was in the works by December 2015, when the DLC for ''3DS'' and ''Wii U'' was in development,<ref name=\"SiSP1\"/> and finished after it was completed.<ref name=\"SiliconeraDev\">{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Alistar |title=Smash Bros. Ultimate Director Sakurai Talks About How The Game Isn\u2019t Just \"Nintendo All-Stars\" Anymore |url=https://www.siliconera.com/2018/12/15/smash-bros-ultimate-director-sakurai-talks-about-how-the-game-isnt-just-nintendo-all-stars-anymore/ |website=[[Siliconera]] |accessdate=December 21, 2018 |date=December 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222082157/https://www.siliconera.com/2018/12/15/smash-bros-ultimate-director-sakurai-talks-about-how-the-game-isnt-just-nintendo-all-stars-anymore/ |archive-date=December 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Staff gathering was done soon afterward.<ref name=\"SiSP1\">{{cite journal |title=Smash is Special \u2013 Part 1 |journal=[[Famitsu]] |date=June 21, 2018 |issue=557 |location=Japan |language=Japanese |medium=Interview with [[Masahiro Sakurai]]}}</ref> The development period was shorter compared to previous entries in the series.<ref name=\"NLifeInter\">{{cite web |last1=Bowling |first1=Steve |title=Feature: Talking Super Smash Bros. Ultimate With Nintendo's Bill Trinen And Nate Bihldorff |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/07/feature_talking_super_smash_bros_ultimate_with_nintendos_bill_trinen_and_nate_bihldorff |website=[[Nintendo Life]] |accessdate=September 20, 2018 |date=July 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920234817/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/07/feature_talking_super_smash_bros_ultimate_with_nintendos_bill_trinen_and_nate_bihldorff |archive-date=September 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Hatena (company)|Hatena]] also assisted with the development of some elements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hatenacorp.jp/press/release/entry/2018/12/07/083000|title=\u306f\u3066\u306a\u3001Nintendo Switch\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u300c\u5927\u4e71\u95d8\u30b9\u30de\u30c3\u30b7\u30e5\u30d6\u30e9\u30b6\u30fc\u30ba SPECIAL\u300d\u306e\u4e00\u90e8\u6a5f\u80fd\u306e\u958b\u767a\u306b\u5354\u529b|website=Hatenacorp.jp|language=ja|access-date=December 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206234619/http://hatenacorp.jp/press/release/entry/2018/12/07/083000|archive-date=December 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Sakurai, producing a ''Super Smash Bros.'' game for the Switch was the last request that former Nintendo president [[Satoru Iwata]] had given him before Iwata's death in 2015, leading Sakurai to feel compelled to make the game the best possible product he could to respect him.<ref name=\"vgc jga2019\">{{cite web | url = https://www.videogameschronicle.com/news/sakurai-acknowledges-iwata-in-japan-game-awards-speech/ | title = Sakurai acknowledges Iwata in Japan Game Awards speech | first =Tom | last = Ivan | date = September 13, 2019 | accessdate = September 14, 2019 | work = [[Video Games Chronicle]] }}</ref>  Sakurai sought to include every character from previous games, as to not disappoint fans.<ref name=\"GIdev\"/> However, he knew this would be a complex problem for both development and licensing;<ref name=\"verge sakurai\" /> it would also drastically increase the cost of development. The return of Bandai and Sora made it easier for this to happen.<ref name=\"SiSP2\">{{cite journal |title=Smash is Special \u2013 Part 2 |journal=[[Famitsu]] |date=June 28, 2018 |issue=558 |location=Japan |language=Japanese |medium=Interview with [[Masahiro Sakurai]]}}</ref> Sakurai also wanted to adjust character abilities as to speed up the game,<ref name=\"verge sakurai\" /> although not to an extent to which it would alienate players unfamiliar with the series.<ref name=\"SiSP1\"/> Sakurai knew that ''Ultimate'' was a core game for Nintendo and that it had a dedicated player base that he did not want to disappoint, and believed that completing this goal was necessary to satisfy the fan base.<ref name=\"verge sakurai\" /> Sakurai was also faced with the decision to create a completely new game system or build off of pre-existing ones; he chose to build off pre-existing ones because there would only be about a third of the characters he desired in the final game.<ref name=\"SiSP1\"/> All the returning characters' abilities had to be re-[[game balance|balanced]] so they could work in ''Ultimate''.<ref name=\"NLifeInter\"/> Originally, gameplay would differ between the Switch's docked and handheld modes, but Sakurai scrapped this because the system's screen in handheld mode was better than he thought.<ref name=\"SiliconeraDev\"/> Sakurai believed this would be the only ''Smash'' game to have the full roster of returning characters, calling the effort to include the characters, music, stage settings, and other elements as \"unprecedented\", and cautioned that future series games would likely be smaller in scope. However, Sakurai wants to add as many fighters as possible within ''Ultimate'' through DLC.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.videogameschronicle.com/news/sakurai-no-way-future-smash-bros-games-will-have-as-many-fighters-as-ultimate/ | title = Sakurai: \u2018No way\u2019 future Smash Bros games will have as many fighters as Ultimate | first = Andy | last = Robinson | date = September 11, 2019 | accessdate = September 11, 2019 | work = [[Video Games Chronicle]] }}</ref>\n\nVoice lines recorded by [[David Hayter]] for the character Snake were re-used for ''Ultimate'', despite Hayter having been replaced in ''[[Metal Gear Solid V]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/e3-2018/2018/06/12/david-hayter-is-voicing-snake-for-his-return-in-super-smash-bros-ultimate|title=David Hayter Is Voicing Snake For His Return In Super Smash Bros. Ultimate - Game Informer|work=Game Informer|access-date=June 12, 2018|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612211303/https://www.gameinformer.com/e3-2018/2018/06/12/david-hayter-is-voicing-snake-for-his-return-in-super-smash-bros-ultimate|archivedate=June 12, 2018}}</ref> [[Xander Mobus]], who provided the voice as the announcer, [[Master Hand]], and Crazy Hand in ''Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS'' and ''Wii U'' also made a return to this game with new voice clips.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/XanderMobusVO/status/1006652458104307714|title=So I guess there was a gaming conference or something with some cool stuff announced? Either way...I'M BACK, BABY!|last=Mobus|first=Xander|date=2018-06-12|website=@xandermobusvo|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref> The addition of Ridley from ''Metroid'' as a playable character has been something that the ''Super Smash Bros.'' community had been requesting from the series for some time. In 2008, Sakurai had said that he knew Ridley was a high-demand character but thought that he was \"impossible\" to add unless they were able to sacrifice the character's size for balancing purposes.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/why-smash-bros-players-are-so-obsessed-with-ridley-1635048910 | title = Why Super Smash Bros Players Are So Obsessed With Ridley | first = Nathan | last = Grayson | date = September 15, 2014 | accessdate = June 23, 2018 | work = [[Kotaku]] | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180619103240/https://kotaku.com/why-smash-bros-players-are-so-obsessed-with-ridley-1635048910 | archivedate = June 19, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> So Ridley could be included in the game, Sakurai studied the art of the character and redesigned him so he could stand upright.<ref name=\"NLifeInter\"/> All characters were chosen at the beginning of development except Incineroar, who had not been created yet;<ref name=\"IGNdev\">{{cite web |last1=Santagelo |first1=Nick |title=Super Smash Bros. Director Talks Character Process and Development |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/11/21/super-smash-bros-director-talks-character-process-and-development |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=December 23, 2018 |date=November 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223211557/https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/11/21/super-smash-bros-director-talks-character-process-and-development |archive-date=December 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> the team instead left a space open for a ''Sun and Moon'' Pok\u00e9mon. The Inklings' ink [[game mechanic|mechanic]] proved challenging to implement due to the way it interacts with environments.<ref name=\"SiliconeraDev\"/>\n\nThe team built ''Ultimate'' from scratch with new assets and content. Localization manager Nate Bihldorff stated that the game significantly upgraded lighting effects and texture rendering from the [[game engine]] of the ''Wii U'' version.<ref name=\"usgamer engine\">{{cite web |url = https://www.usgamer.net/articles/nintendo-smash-bros-ultimate-interview-brand-new-game-than-wii-u |title = Nintendo on Whether Smash Bros. Ultimate is Just a Wii U Update: \"It's Built From the Ground Up\" |first = Kat |last = Bailey |date = June 13, 2018 |accessdate = June 13, 2018 |website = [[USGamer]] |url-status=live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180614232901/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/nintendo-smash-bros-ultimate-interview-brand-new-game-than-wii-u |archivedate = June 14, 2018 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> The new World of Light mode was inspired by ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl|Brawl]]''{{'s}} (2008) Subspace Emissary, and Sakurai chose to start it with a cataclysmic event because he thought it would leave a greater impact on players.<ref name=\"SiliconeraDev\"/> The team conceived the Spirits mechanic because they wanted to create an enjoyable single-player mode but did not have enough resources to create [[3D modeling|character models]]. While it did not let them tell stories for individual fighters or create new locations and rules, the Spirits let them use a variety of characters and assets.<ref name=\"GIdev\">{{cite web |last1=Shea |first1=Brian |title=Masahiro Sakurai Talks Piranha Plant, Spirits, And 20 Years Of Super Smash Bros. |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/interview/2018/11/21/masahiro-sakurai-talks-piranha-plant-spirits-and-20-years-of-super-smash-bros |website=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=December 23, 2018 |date=November 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224023828/https://www.gameinformer.com/interview/2018/11/21/masahiro-sakurai-talks-piranha-plant-spirits-and-20-years-of-super-smash-bros |archive-date=December 24, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> One part of the team chose Spirits to include in the game and had to thoroughly research them. According to Sakurai, the Spirits mode was essential for using various franchises.<ref name=\"SiliconeraDev\"/> \n\n=== Music ===\nLike previous games in the series, ''Ultimate'' features several well-known video game music composers and arrangers providing a mix of original music and rearrangements of various tracks for the represented franchises, with over 800 tracks in total.<ref name=\"Music\">{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Tamoor |title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Soundtrack Has Over 800 Songs |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimate-soundtrack-has-over-800-/1100-6461025/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=September 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824200013/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimate-soundtrack-has-over-800-/1100-6461025/ |archive-date=August 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Khan |first1=Imran |title=Have You Been Listening To The Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Music Samples? |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/psa/2018/07/10/have-you-been-listening-to-the-super-smash-bros-ultimate-music-samples |website=Game Informer |accessdate=September 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920011314/https://www.gameinformer.com/psa/2018/07/10/have-you-been-listening-to-the-super-smash-bros-ultimate-music-samples |archive-date=September 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> New to ''Ultimate'' is the tying of tracks to franchises instead of individual stages, as well as the ability to create custom [[playlist]]s to listen to outside of the game when the Switch is in handheld mode.<ref name=\"Music\"/> Sakurai stated that he began contacting composers over a year before release, providing them with a database of over a thousand suggested track ideas.<ref name=\"Music2\">{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Alistair |title=Masahiro Sakurai On The Process Of Including Music In Smash Bros. Ultimate |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2018/09/07/masahiro-sakurai-on-the-process-of-including-music-in-smash-bros-ultimate/ |website=Siliconera |accessdate=September 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920011355/http://www.siliconera.com/2018/09/07/masahiro-sakurai-on-the-process-of-including-music-in-smash-bros-ultimate/ |archive-date=September 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In addition, he allowed them to submit their own personal favorites, with those choices being given priority for inclusion.<ref name=\"Music2\"/> While Sakurai oversaw the process and preferred that the music retain the spirit of the original games, the direction of them was generally handled by the composers themselves.<ref name=\"Music2\"/> The main theme, \"Lifelight,\" composed by [[Hideki Sakamoto]], is the basis of most of the game's original music.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sounders |first1=Mike |title=Check out all the new music from yesterday's Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Direct |url=https://www.destructoid.com/check-out-all-the-new-music-from-yesterday-s-super-smash-bros-ultimate-direct-529553.phtml |website=Destructoid |accessdate=November 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409121330/https://www.destructoid.com/check-out-all-the-new-music-from-yesterday-s-super-smash-bros-ultimate-direct-529553.phtml |archive-date=April 9, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Craddock |first1=Ryan |title=Meet The Talent Behind Super Smash Bros. Ultimate's 'LifeLight' Theme Song |url=https://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/11/meet_the_talent_behind_super_smash_bros_ultimates_lifelight_theme_song |website=Nintendo Life |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Downloadable content ===\nAs with previous entries, Nintendo planned to offer new fighters through DLC; however, unlike with the previous ''3DS'' and ''Wii U'' version where players could request which characters they wished to see in the game, Nintendo chose which characters they would add by November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/7/18071684/super-smash-bros-ultimate-dlc-fighters-lineup-confirmed|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate DLC lineup has already been decided|last=McWhertor|first=Michael|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=November 7, 2018|accessdate=November 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108025626/https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/7/18071684/super-smash-bros-ultimate-dlc-fighters-lineup-confirmed|archive-date=November 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Sakurai believed that despite characters like Joker, the first announced DLC fighter, not necessarily being from games usually associated with Nintendo, they were added due to being \"emblematic\" of the types of characters they wanted to add to ''Ultimate'', adding that they \"bring just a whole different level of fun and enjoyment for players\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/12/07/nintendo-persona-5s-joker-is-emblematic-of-smash-bros-ultimates-dlc-approach | title = Nintendo: Persona 5's Joker is 'Emblematic' of Smash Bros. Ultimate's DLC Approach | first = Andrew | last = Goldfarb | date = December 7, 2018 | accessdate = December 10, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190212195414/https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/12/07/nintendo-persona-5s-joker-is-emblematic-of-smash-bros-ultimates-dlc-approach | archive-date = February 12, 2019 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The Piranha Plant was chosen as a DLC character because Sakurai wanted to add diversity to the roster.<ref name=\"IGNdev\"/> [[Phil Spencer (business executive)|Phil Spencer]], the head of [[Xbox]], stated that negotiating the inclusion of Banjo and Kazooie, a property owned by [[Microsoft]] through its acquisition of [[Rare (company)|Rare]], was \"an easy deal to make\" thanks to Microsoft's strong partnership with Nintendo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/xbox-boss-phil-spencer-says-banjo-in-smash-was-an-easy-1835418742|title=Xbox Boss Phil Spencer Says Banjo In Smash Was An Easy Deal To Make|last=Totilo|first=Stephen|date=June 10, 2019|website=[[Kotaku]]|language=en-US|access-date=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[File:Nintendo booth (29723948888).jpg|right|thumb|Attendees at the 2018 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] playing a demo of ''Ultimate'']]\n\n''Ultimate'' was teased during a [[Nintendo Direct]] presentation on March 8, 2018, under the [[working title]] ''Super Smash Bros.'', with the release year shown to be 2018. Nintendo formally announced the game at [[E3 2018]], revealing that the full roster of characters from past games would be included, as well as its release date.<ref name=\"Kotaku\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Super Smash Bros. is coming to Nintendo Switch |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/8/17097680/smash-bros-switch-release-date |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=March 8, 2018 |date=March 8, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309160350/https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/8/17097680/smash-bros-switch-release-date |archivedate=March 9, 2018 }}</ref> [[Game demo|Demo]] versions were playable at E3 in June and at the [[San Diego Comic-Con]] the following month.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Craddock |first1=Ryan |title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Will Be Playable At San Diego Comic-Con This Week |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/07/super_smash_bros_ultimate_will_be_playable_at_san_diego_comic-con_this_week |website=[[Nintendo Life]] |accessdate=November 1, 2018 |date=July 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103131211/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/07/super_smash_bros_ultimate_will_be_playable_at_san_diego_comic-con_this_week |archive-date=November 3, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Foxx |first1=Chris |title=E3: Nintendo's Super Smash Bros Ultimate battle-tested |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/technology-44465166/e3-nintendo-s-super-smash-bros-ultimate-battle-tested |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=November 1, 2018 |date=June 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103103456/https://www.bbc.com/news/av/technology-44465166/e3-nintendo-s-super-smash-bros-ultimate-battle-tested |archive-date=November 3, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[IGN]]'' nominated ''Ultimate'' for its Best Game of E3 2018 award; the game won Best Nintendo Switch Game from both ''IGN'' and [[Gamescom]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/06/15/best-of-e3-2018-awards|title=Best of E3 2018 Awards|date=June 15, 2018|accessdate=November 24, 2018|publisher=[[IGN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125074146/https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/06/15/best-of-e3-2018-awards|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/gamescom-award-2018-nominees-include-marvels-spider-man-super-smash-bros-ultimate/|title=Gamescom 2018 award winners include Marvel's Spider-Man, Super Smash Bros. Ultimate|date=August 22, 2018|accessdate=November 24, 2018|publisher=[[CNET]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181230080413/https://www.cnet.com/news/gamescom-award-2018-nominees-include-marvels-spider-man-super-smash-bros-ultimate/|archive-date=December 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Two Nintendo Direct presentations in 2018, one on August 8 and another one on November 1, were devoted to the game, revealing new characters, stages, and game modes.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goslen |first1=Austen |title=Top 5 reveals from today\u2019s Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Nintendo Direct |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/1/18051930/super-smash-bros-ultimate-nintendo-direct-characters-dlc-announcements |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=November 1, 2018 |date=November 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181101163858/https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/1/18051930/super-smash-bros-ultimate-nintendo-direct-characters-dlc-announcements |archive-date=November 1, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kuchera |first1=Ben |title=Super Smash Bros. Direct: Watch it here |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/8/8/17657686/nintendo-direct-smash-bros-live-stream-date-start-time |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=November 1, 2018 |date=August 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103092115/https://www.polygon.com/2018/8/8/17657686/nintendo-direct-smash-bros-live-stream-date-start-time |archive-date=November 3, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nNintendo released ''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'' worldwide on December 7, 2018.<ref name=\"ignrev\"/> In addition to the standard retail version, a special edition containing a ''Super Smash Bros.''-themed [[Nintendo Switch Pro Controller]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/8/27/17786984/super-smash-bros-ultimate-nintendo-switch-pro-controller-bundle-best-buy-price|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate is getting a limited edition Pro controller|work=Polygon|access-date=August 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827201608/https://www.polygon.com/2018/8/27/17786984/super-smash-bros-ultimate-nintendo-switch-pro-controller-bundle-best-buy-price|archive-date=August 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and a Switch with a download code was also released.<ref>{{cite web |last1=G. Macy |first1=Seth |title=Here Are All the Nintendo Switch Bundles Coming Out This Year |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/09/18/fortnite-switch-bundle-release-date-preorder |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=September 19, 2018 |date=September 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918224007/https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/09/18/fortnite-switch-bundle-release-date-preorder |archive-date=September 18, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> An additional special edition contained a pair of ''Super Smash Bros.''-themed [[Joy-Con]] as well as a Switch console, a ''Super Smash Bros.''-themed dock, and a download code for the game.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Lawler|first1=Richard|url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/09/13/switch-super-smash-bros-ultimate-bundle/|title=Switch 'Super Smash Bros. Ultimate' set bundles system and game for $360|work=Engadget|access-date=October 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017123548/https://www.engadget.com/2018/09/13/switch-super-smash-bros-ultimate-bundle/|archive-date=October 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[GameCube controller]] with the ''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'' logo was released on November 2, 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/06/gamecube_controllers_will_be_compatible_with_super_smash_bros_ultimate|title=GameCube Controllers Will Be Compatible With Super Smash Bros. Ultimate|work=Nintendo Life|accessdate=October 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719143055/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/06/gamecube_controllers_will_be_compatible_with_super_smash_bros_ultimate|archive-date=July 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOne of the game's new additions had the character [[Mr. Game & Watch]] assuming the appearance of a feather- and loincloth-wearing [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] when using one of his attacks\u2014a reference to [[List of Game & Watch games#Fire Attack|''Fire Attack'']] (1982), in which players controlled a [[cowboy]] defending his fort from attacking [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|natives]]. Some series fans saw this as racist, leading to Nintendo apologizing and removing the animation in an update shortly after release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-11-07-nintendo-to-remove-native-american-reference-in-super-smash-bros-ultimate|title=Nintendo to remove Native American references in Super Smash Bros. Ultimate|website=[[Eurogamer]]|date=November 7, 2018|accessdate=November 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107171944/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-11-07-nintendo-to-remove-native-american-reference-in-super-smash-bros-ultimate|archive-date=November 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Two weeks before its release, a leaked copy of the game was distributed across the internet. Nintendo took steps to issue copyright strikes on YouTube videos using [[data mined]] content, while fans worked to isolate [[Spoiler (media)|spoilers]], particularly the World of Light story mode, from those that had played the leaked version.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/27/18113487/super-smash-bros-ultimate-leaks-spoilers | title = Why Super Smash Bros. fans can\u2019t stand \u2018disrespectful\u2019 spoilers | first = Allegra | last = Frank | date = November 27, 2018 | accessdate = November 28, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181128021603/https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/27/18113487/super-smash-bros-ultimate-leaks-spoilers | archive-date = November 28, 2018 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = 93/100<ref name=\"mc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/super-smash-bros-ultimate|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate for Switch Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109041136/https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/super-smash-bros-ultimate|archive-date=January 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 9.5/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Carter|first=Chris|date=December 6, 2018|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-super-smash-bros-ultimate-532682.phtml|title=Review: Super Smash Bros Ultimate|publisher=[[Destructoid]]|accessdate=December 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207111607/https://www.destructoid.com/review-super-smash-bros-ultimate-532682.phtml|archive-date=December 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Edge = 9/10<ref name=\"edge_review\">{{cite magazine|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate|magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]| issue=327 |publication-date=December 6, 2018 |pages=102\u2013103 |issn=1350-1593}}</ref>\n| EGM = 9.5/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Slead|first=Evan|date=December 6, 2018|url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/super-smash-bros-ultimate-review|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate review|publisher=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]|accessdate=December 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207111620/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/super-smash-bros-ultimate-review/|archive-date=December 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| EuroG = Essential<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-12-07-super-smash-bros-ultimate-review-a-messy-magical-festival-of-video-games|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate review - a messy, magical festival of video games|publisher=Eurogamer|accessdate=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212014636/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-12-07-super-smash-bros-ultimate-review-a-messy-magical-festival-of-video-games|archive-date=December 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Fam = 38/40<ref>\n{{cite web |first=Sal |last=Romano |title=Famitsu Review Scores: Issue 1568 |url=https://gematsu.com/2018/12/famitsu-review-scores-issue-1568 |website=Gematsu |accessdate=December 18, 2018 |date=December 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219042800/https://gematsu.com/2018/12/famitsu-review-scores-issue-1568 |archive-date=December 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n</ref>\n| GI = 9.5/10<ref name=\"gi_review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/review/super-smash-bros-ultimate/a-raucous-clash-reunion|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Review|work=[[Game Informer]]|first=Jeff|last=Cork|date=December 7, 2018|accessdate=December 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210154705/https://www.gameinformer.com/review/super-smash-bros-ultimate/a-raucous-clash-reunion|archive-date=December 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GamePro = 87/100<ref>\n{{cite web|last=Cherdchupan|first=Michael|date=December 10, 2018|url=https://www.gamepro.de/spiele/super-smash-bros-ultimate,wertung,172,9389.html|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate im Test - Geniales Pr\u00fcgelfestival mit einem Online-Tiefschlag|publisher=[[GamePro]]|accessdate=December 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409121330/https://www.gamepro.de/spiele/super-smash-bros-ultimate,wertung,172,9389.html|archive-date=April 9, 2019|url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Garst|first=Aron|date=December 6, 2018|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/uk/super-smash-bros-ultimate-review/|title=Super Smash Bros Ultimate Review|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|accessdate=December 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206192622/https://www.gamesradar.com/uk/super-smash-bros-ultimate-review/|archive-date=December 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 9/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Tran|first=Edmond|date=December 6, 2018|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/super-smash-bros-ultimate-review-in-progress/1900-6417051|title=Super Smash Bros Ultimate Review|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=December 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206161420/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/super-smash-bros-ultimate-review-in-progress/1900-6417051/|archive-date=December 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| IGN = 9.4/10<ref name=\"ignrev\">{{cite web|last=Marks|first=Tom|date=December 6, 2018|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2018/12/06/super-smash-bros-ultimate-review|title=Super Smash Bros Ultimate Review|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=December 6, 2018}}</ref>\n| JXV = 18/20<ref name=\"jeuxvideo_review\"/>\n| NLife = 10/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Olney|first=Alex|date=December 6, 2018|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/nintendo-switch/super_smash_bros_ultimate|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Review|publisher=[[Nintendo Life]]|accessdate=December 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206215942/http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/nintendo-switch/super_smash_bros_ultimate|archive-date=December 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| NWR = 9/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/49135/super-smash-bros-ultimate-switch-review|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate review|publisher=Nintendo World Report|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n| USG = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey|first=Kat|date=December 7, 2018|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimate-review-12072018|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Review|publisher=[[USgamer]]|accessdate=December 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209165152/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimate-review-12072018|archive-date=December 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}{{Expand section|The review section is too short, more details could be added, and the names of the reviewers should be shown|date=January 2020}}''Ultimate'' received \"universal acclaim\" from critics, according to the [[review aggregator]] platform [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"mc\" /> The French video game website ''[[Jeuxvideo.com]]'' called it the best game in the series, praising the improved gameplay, larger cast of characters, stages, options, soundtrack, which \"brilliantly mix gargantuan content with nostalgia\".<ref name=\"jeuxvideo_review\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/test/969075/super-smash-bros-ultimate-le-meilleur-episode-de-la-serie.htm|title=Test : Super Smash Bros. Ultimate : Le meilleur \u00e9pisode de la s\u00e9rie|author1=Anagund|author2=Epyon|date=December 6, 2018|accessdate=December 6, 2018|publisher=Webedia|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206192624/http://www.jeuxvideo.com/test/969075/super-smash-bros-ultimate-le-meilleur-episode-de-la-serie.htm|archive-date=December 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''IGN'' agreed and called it the most complete ''Super Smash Bros.'' yet.<ref name=\"ignrev\" /> Critics lauded the huge cast of characters and levels, new game modes, and combining of the best elements from its predecessors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/smash-bros-ultimate-reviews-roundup/1100-6463718/|title=Smash Bros. Ultimate Reviews Roundup|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|date=December 7, 2018|website=Gamespot.com|accessdate=December 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209123639/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/smash-bros-ultimate-reviews-roundup/1100-6463718/|archive-date=December 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the game's online mode received criticism for its technical performance and matchmaking. Many players found significant [[lag]] affecting their games, even when using wired connections over wireless, while the game's matchmaking features did not adhere to players' criteria, with players frequently playing matches with rule sets they did not choose. The matchmaking process was further criticized for making it difficult for friends to join matches over random players, and not allowing multiple local players to join in online matches.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.polygon.com/2018/12/11/18136617/super-smash-bros-ultimate-online-issues-multiplayer | title= Super Smash Bros. Ultimate\u2019s online modes are turning players away | first= Allegra | last= Frank | date= December 11, 2018 | accessdate= December 11, 2018 | work= [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181212012023/https://www.polygon.com/2018/12/11/18136617/super-smash-bros-ultimate-online-issues-multiplayer | archive-date= December 12, 2018 | url-status=live | df= mdy-all }}</ref> There had been so many complaints on ''Ultimate''{{'s}} [[Reddit#Subreddits|subreddit]] that the administrators forwarded all complaints to a separate thread.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/super-smash-bros-still-cant-get-online-right-1830993555|title=Super Smash Bros. Still Can't Get Online Right|first=Cecilia|last=D'Anastasio|date=December 10, 2018|work=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=December 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211011019/https://kotaku.com/super-smash-bros-still-cant-get-online-right-1830993555|archive-date=December 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Sales===\nIn November 2018, Nintendo announced ''Ultimate'' was the most preordered game for the Switch and in the series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/11/super_smash_bros_ultimate_is_the_best_pre-selling_game_of_the_series_to_date_and_on_switch|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Is The Best Pre-Selling Game Of The Series To Date, And On Switch|first=Ryan|last=Craddock|date=November 23, 2018|work=[[Nintendo Life]]|accessdate=November 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125115425/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/11/super_smash_bros_ultimate_is_the_best_pre-selling_game_of_the_series_to_date_and_on_switch|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[The Association for UK Interactive Entertainment]] reported that ''Ultimate'' was the fastest-selling Switch and ''Super Smash Bros.'' game in the United Kingdom, with physical launch sales 302% higher than those for ''Super Smash Bros. for Wii U'', 233% higher than those for ''3DS'', and 62.5% higher than those for ''Brawl''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-12-09-uk-charts-super-smash-bros-ultimate-is-the-fastest-selling-smash-bros-of-all-time|title=UK Charts: Super Smash Bros Ultimate is the fastest-selling Smash Bros of all time|first=Christopher|last=Dring|date=December 9, 2018|work=Gameindustry.biz|accessdate=December 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210000412/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-12-09-uk-charts-super-smash-bros-ultimate-is-the-fastest-selling-smash-bros-of-all-time|archive-date=December 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In its first three days on sale in Japan, the game sold 1.2 million copies, outselling [[Pok\u00e9mon: Let's Go, Pikachu! and Let's Go, Eevee!|''Pok\u00e9mon: Let's Go, Pikachu!'' and ''Let's Go, Eevee!'']] and ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]]'' in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/12/smash_bros_ultimate_sold_1_2_million_copies_in_japan_during_launch_week|title=Smash Bros. Ultimate Sold 1.2 Million Copies In Japan During Launch Week|first=Liam|last=Doolan|date=December 11, 2018|work=[[Nintendo Life]]|accessdate=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212084658/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/12/smash_bros_ultimate_sold_1_2_million_copies_in_japan_during_launch_week|archive-date=December 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWithin 11 days of its release, ''Ultimate'' had sold more than three million copies within the United States, making it the fastest-selling Switch game in the country.<ref name=\"variety ssbu\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/super-smash-bros-ultimate-sales-1203092096/|title=\u2018Super Smash Bros. Ultimate\u2019 Fastest Selling Nintendo Switch Game|first=Brian|last=Crecente|date=December 18, 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=December 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181218160252/https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/super-smash-bros-ultimate-sales-1203092096/|archive-date=December 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It was similarly the fastest-selling Switch game as well as the fastest-selling game for any Nintendo console in Europe based on the first 11-day sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/12/18/super-smash-bros-ultimate-fastest-selling-nintendo-home-console-game-of-all-time/|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate is the fastest-selling Nintendo home console game of all time in Europe|first=Shabana|last=Arif|date=December 18, 2018|work=[[VG247]]|accessdate=December 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219002512/https://www.vg247.com/2018/12/18/super-smash-bros-ultimate-fastest-selling-nintendo-home-console-game-of-all-time/|archive-date=December 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It was estimated that the game sold and shipped over five million copies within its first three days of release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/333375/Smash_Bros_Ultimate_worldwide_sales_topped_5M_in_first_week.php|title=Smash Bros. Ultimate worldwide sales topped 5M in first week|first=Chris|last=Kerr|date=December 20, 2018|work=[[Gamasutra]]|accessdate=December 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220230519/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/333375/Smash_Bros_Ultimate_worldwide_sales_topped_5M_in_first_week.php|archive-date=December 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Within three weeks, ''Ultimate'' became the fifth bestselling Switch game in the United Kingdom, surpassing the sales of ''[[Splatoon 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/12/uk_charts_super_smash_bros_ultimate_overtakes_splatoon_2_lifetime_sales_in_uk|title=UK Charts: Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Overtakes Splatoon 2 Lifetime Sales In UK|first=Ryan|last=Craddock|date=December 24, 2018|work=[[Nintendo Life]]|accessdate=December 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224220350/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/12/uk_charts_super_smash_bros_ultimate_overtakes_splatoon_2_lifetime_sales_in_uk|archive-date=December 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2019, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] reported that ''Ultimate'' was their highest selling video game product of 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/2019/01/02/super-smash-bros-ultimate-tops-amazon-best-seller-list-nintendo-switch/|title=\u2018Super Smash Bros. Ultimate\u2019 Tops Amazon\u2019s Best-Selling Games List For 2018|first=Robert|last=-Workman|work=Comicbook.com|date=January 1, 2019|accessdate=January 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102082710/https://comicbook.com/gaming/2019/01/02/super-smash-bros-ultimate-tops-amazon-best-seller-list-nintendo-switch/|archive-date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> with Nintendo officially announcing that the game had shipped over 12.08 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-31/nintendo-beats-profit-estimates-cuts-switch-shipments-target | title = Nintendo Tops Profit Estimates, Cuts Switch Shipments Target | first = Yuji | last = Nakamura | date = January 31, 2019 | accessdate = January 31, 2019 | work = [[Bloomberg L.P.]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013305/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-31/nintendo-beats-profit-estimates-cuts-switch-shipments-target | archive-date = February 1, 2019 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''Ultimate'' was also Nintendo's fastest-selling game of all time until being surpassed by [[Pok\u00e9mon Sword and Shield|''Pok\u00e9mon Sword'' and ''Shield'']] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vg247.com/2019/01/31/super-smash-bros-ultimate-is-the-fastest-selling-nintendo-game-ever/ | title = Super Smash Bros. Ultimate is the fastest selling Nintendo game ever | first = Shabana | last = Arif | date = January 31, 2019 | accessdate = January 31, 2019 | work = [[VG247]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190201020250/https://www.vg247.com/2019/01/31/super-smash-bros-ultimate-is-the-fastest-selling-nintendo-game-ever/ | archive-date = February 1, 2019 | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/21/20975624/pokemon-sword-and-shield-sales-switch-record | title = Pok\u00e9mon Sword and Shield is the fastest-selling Nintendo Switch game yet | first = Sam | last = Byford | date = November 21, 2019 | accessdate = November 25, 2019 | work = The Verge}}</ref> By December 2019, the game had sold over 17.68 million copies worldwide, making it the best-selling fighting game of all time,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dahlgren |first1=Lisa |title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate is the best-selling fighting game |url=https://www.gamereactor.eu/news/752843/Super+Smash+Bros+Ultimate+is+the+bestselling+fighting+game/ |website=Game Reactor |accessdate=May 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/finance/software/index.html |title=Top Selling Title Sales Units |website=[[Nintendo]] |date=December 31, 2019 |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref> surpassing the record of ''[[Street Fighter II]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bankhurst |first1=Adam |title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Is The Best-Selling Fighting Game Ever |url=https://ign.com/articles/2019/11/04/super-smash-bros-ultimate-is-the-best-selling-fighting-game-ever |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nThe game won the award for \"Best Nintendo Switch Game\", \"Best Fighting Game\", and \"Best Multiplayer Game\" in [[IGN]]'s Best of 2018 Awards, whereas its other nominations were for \"Game of the Year\" and \"Best Video Game Music\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/best-of-2018|title=IGN'S Best of 2018|date=December 10, 2018|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113235150/https://www.ign.com/best-of-2018|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitabl