{"title_page": "Kay Brown (artist)", "text_new": "{{for|the talent scout |Kay B. Barrett}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Kay Brown\n| image         = Kay_Brown_head.jpg \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth-date |1932}}\n| birth_place   = [[New York City]]\n| death_date    = {{Death year and age|2012|1932}}\n| death_place   = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| nationality   = \n| spouse        = \n| field         = [[Painting]]<br/>[[Printmaking]]<br/>[[Collage]]\n| training      = \n| movement      = [[Black Arts Movement]]\n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n| elected       = \n| website       = \n| bgcolour      =\n}} \n'''Kay Brown (Artist) ''' (1932-2012) was an [[African Americans|African American]] artist and one of the founders of the [[Where We At]] Black women [[Artist collective|artists' collective]] in New York City.  Brown's work was featured in the \"We Wanted a Revolution\" exhibition at the Brooklyn Museum.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/20/arts/design/review-we-wanted-a-revolution-black-radical-women-brooklyn-museum.html|title=To Be Black, Female and Fed Up With the Mainstream|last=Cotter|first=Holland|date=2017-04-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-11-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fmOpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA120&lpg=PA120&dq=New+York+Feminist+Art+Collective+Kay+Brown&source=bl&ots=gnxkLUINhd&sig=h_U3FLkIw2ORmc9a7Of3guV8ikc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjElLf6-sjXAhVJrVQKHUm9COo4ChDoAQglMAA#v=onepage&q=New%20York%20Feminist%20Art%20Collective%20Kay%20Brown&f=false|title=Entering the Picture: Judy Chicago, The Fresno Feminist Art Program, and the Collective Visions of Women Artists|last=Fields|first=Jill|date=2012-02-27|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136638923|location=|pages=120|language=en}}</ref> She was also a member of the [[Weusi Artist Collective]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.retirement-living.com/an-inspirational-artist/|title=An Inspirational Artist: Active Adult {{!}} Retirement Living|website=www.retirement-living.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref> based in [[Harlem]] during the 1960s and 1970s.<ref name=\"Weusi\">{{cite journal|last1=Brown|first1=Kay|title=The Weusi Artists|journal=NKA: A Journal of Contemporary African Art|date=Spring 2012|volume=2012|issue=30|page=63|doi=10.1215/10757163-1496471}}</ref>  \n\n== Career ==\nBrown was a staff member at the [[Medgar Evers College]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Allen|first1=Catherine|title=Transformations: Women in Art 70's-80's, New York Coliseum, March 5-9, 1981|date=1981|publisher=New York Feminist Art Institute / ARTEXPO N.Y.|location=New York|page=9}}</ref> and an assistant professor at the [[Anne Arundel Community College]] from 1989-1990. Brown also wrote a young adult novel, ''Willy's Summer Dream'', which was published in 1989.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/willyssummerdrea00brow|title=Willy's Summer Dream|last=Brown|first=Kay|date=1989-09-01|publisher=Harcourt Childrens Books|isbn=9780152006457|edition=1st|location=San Diego|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/willyssummerdrea00brow|title=Willy's summer dream|last=Brown|first=Kay|date=1989|publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich|isbn=0152006451|location=San Diego|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-15-200645-7|title=Children's Book Review: Willy's Summer Dream by Kay Brown, Author Houghton Mifflin Harcourt P $13.95 (132p) ISBN 978-0-15-200645-7|work=PublishersWeekly.com|access-date=2017-11-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''The Black Soldier'', 1969<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2bElDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA106&lpg=PA106&dq=%22Kay+Brown%22+%22Black+Soldier%22&source=bl&ots=LlgT-Z86A0&sig=_jDpn7aUZmSkX8Q23Y0oahP6rwc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi4i6u2-sjXAhVEllQKHTk9AvYQ6AEIOzAE#v=onepage&q=%22Kay%20Brown%22%20%22Black%20Soldier%22&f=false|title=American Artists Against War, 1935 2010|last=McCarthy|first=David|date=2015-07-07|publisher=Univ of California Press|isbn=9780520286702|location=|pages=106|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Willowbrook'', 1972<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/kay-brown/willowbrook-WGlADjUT0gRY1fPvxfPPow2|title=Willowbrook by KayBrown|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref>\n* ''First Kick of Life'' (Color etching and aquatint on paper, circa 1974), in the collection of the [[Brooklyn Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/objects/210673|title=First Kick of Life|author=Brooklyn Museum|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref>\n* ''Black Mother and Male Child'', 1974-1975<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/kay-brown/black-mother-and-male-child-ohT1jMPSv_d61HYRPs2IDg2|title=Black Mother and Male Child by KayBrown|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref>\n* ''Everytime I Feel the Spirit'' (Etching, 1979), exhibited in the exhibition ''Transformations: Women in Art 70's-80's'', at the [[New York Coliseum]], March 5\u20139, 1981\n* ''The Devil and His Game'' (Collage, 1968), exhibited in the exhibition ''Tradition and Conflict: Images of a Turbulent Decade, 1963-1973'', at the [[Studio Museum in Harlem]], January 27-June 30, 1985\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n* ''Blackness in Color: Visual Expressions of the Black Arts Movement'', ''1960-Present'', [[Herbert F. Johnson Museum of Art]], [[Cornell University]], August\u2013October, 2000<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=83teYXulg5kC&pg=PA421&lpg=PA421&dq=%22Kay+Brown%22+art+dc&source=bl&ots=zl34w4jWuZ&sig=mbw3QcflzleaTkZfEEuN-NfYZtg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj83t6K58jXAhVmqlQKHWafCPAQ6AEIRzAK#v=onepage&q=%22Kay%20Brown%22%20art%20dc&f=false|title=Creating Black Americans: African-American History and Its Meanings, 1619 to the Present|last=Painter|first=Nell Irvin|date=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195137552|location=|pages=421|language=en}}</ref>\n* Transformations: Women in Art 70's-80's, [[New York Coliseum]], March 5\u20139, 1981\n* ''We Wanted a Revolution: Black Radical Women, 1965-85'', [[Brooklyn Museum]], April 21-September, 2017<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/exhibitions/3347|title=We Wanted a Revolution: Black Radical Women, 1965\u201385 (Exhibition)|author=Brooklyn Museum|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags, these references will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Kay}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:American women painters]]\n[[Category:African-American women artists]]\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:Women printmakers]]\n[[Category:Modern printmakers]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American printmakers]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Medgar Evers College faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the talent scout |Kay B. Barrett}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Kay Brown\n| image         = Kay_Brown_head.jpg \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth-date |1932}}\n| birth_place   = [[New York City]]\n| death_date    = {{Death year and age|2012|1932}}\n| death_place   = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| nationality   = \n| spouse        = \n| field         = [[Painting]]<br/>[[Printmaking]]<br/>[[Collage]]\n| training      = \n| movement      = [[Black Arts Movement]]\n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n| elected       = \n| website       = \n| bgcol