es --->\n[[Category:American women painters]]\n[[Category:African-American women artists]]\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:Women printmakers]]\n[[Category:Modern printmakers]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American printmakers]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Medgar Evers College faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Ugotme 2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a sentence in the opening paragraph regarding the exhibition at the Brooklyn Arts Museum.  Re-worded text in the career section.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kay_Brown_(artist)"}
{"title_page": "Green-backed woodpecker", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of bird in the family Picidae}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Green-backed Woodpecker - Malawi S4E3705.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22680919/0 |title=''Campethera cailliautii'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| taxon = Campethera cailliautii\n| authority = ([[Alfred Malherbe|Malherbe]], 1849)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''green-backed woodpecker''' or '''little spotted woodpecker''' (''Campethera cailliautii''), is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Picidae]]. It is native to large parts of tropical central Africa. It has an extensive range and is an uncommon species, and the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] has rated its conservation status as being of \"[[Least-concern species|least concern]].\"<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==Description==\nThe green-backed woodpecker grows to a length of about {{convert|16|cm|in|1|abbr=on}}. The male has a scarlet crown flecked with black and a bright red nape. The female has a blackish crown spotted with white and a red nape. Both sexes have green upperparts, spotted with cream or yellow, and buff or white underparts, boldly spotted with black, and flanks barred with black. The tail is green, with individual feathers having brownish shafts. There is a white [[supercilium]], and the eye-ring is grey, the iris chestnut, the beak grey tipped with black and the legs and feet grey or olive. The juvenile is similar to the female in appearance, although the nape may have little red.<ref name=Gorman/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe green-backed woodpecker is found in [[Angola]], [[Burundi]], [[Cameroon]], [[Central African Republic]], [[Republic of the Congo]], the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], [[Equatorial Guinea]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Gabon]], [[Ghana]], [[Kenya]], [[Malawi]], [[Mozambique]], [[Nigeria]], [[Rwanda]], [[Somalia]], [[Sudan]], [[Tanzania]], [[Togo]], [[Uganda]], [[Zambia]], and [[Zimbabwe]]. The habitat varies across the range, being variously wet or dry forest, gallery forest or flooded forest, scrub, savannah, coastal woodland, [[palm oil]] plantations, gardens, or wooded villages. This is mostly a lowland bird, but it is found at altitudes of up to {{convert|2100|m|ft|-2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Gorman>{{cite book|author=Gerard Gorman|title=Woodpeckers of the World: The Complete Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9LmnAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA181 |year=2014 |publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-1-4081-4717-7 |pages=181\u2013182}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nThe green-backed woodpecker feeds mainly on ants and termites, which it finds on trees. It often forages in pairs or may form part of small groups of mixed bird species.<ref name=Gorman/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* (Green-backed woodpecker = ) Little spotted woodpecker - [http://sabap2.adu.org.za/docs/sabap1/485.pdf Species text in The Atlas of Southern African Birds]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1264601}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:woodpecker, green-backed}}\n[[Category:Campethera|green-backed woodpecker]]\n[[Category:Birds of East Africa]]\n[[Category:Birds of Central Africa]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1849|green-backed woodpecker]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of bird in the family Picidae}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Green-backed Woodpecker - Malawi S4E3705.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22680919/0 |title=''Campethera cailliautii'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| taxon = Campethera cailliautii\n| authority = ([[Alfred Malherbe|Malherbe]], 1849)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''green-backed woodpecker''' or '''little spotted woodpecker''' (''Campethera cailliautii''), is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Picidae]]. It is native to large parts of tropical central Africa. It has an extremely wide range and is an uncommon species, and the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] has rated its conservation status as being of \"[[Least-concern species|least concern]]\".<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==Description==\nThe green-backed woodpecker grows to a length of about {{convert|16|cm|in|1|abbr=on}}. The male has a scarlet crown flecked with black and a bright red nape. The female has a blackish crown spotted with white, and a red nape. Both sexes have green upper parts, spotted with cream or yellow, and buff or white underparts, boldly spotted with black, and flanks barred with black. The tail is green with individual feathers having brownish shafts. There is a white [[supercilium]], the eye ring is grey, the iris chestnut, the beak grey tipped with black and the legs and feet grey or olive. The juvenile is similar to the female in appearance, although the nape may have little red.<ref name=Gorman/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe green-backed woodpecker is found in [[Angola]], [[Burundi]], [[Cameroon]], [[Central African Republic]], [[Republic of the Congo]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], [[Equatorial Guinea]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Gabon]], [[Ghana]], [[Kenya]], [[Malawi]], [[Mozambique]], [[Nigeria]], [[Rwanda]], [[Somalia]], [[Sudan]], [[Tanzania]], [[Togo]], [[Uganda]], [[Zambia]], and [[Zimbabwe]]. The habitat varies across the range, being variously wet or dry forest, gallery forest or flooded forest, scrub, savannah, coastal woodland, [[palm oil]] plantations, gardens or wooded villages. This is mostly a lowland bird, but it is found at altitudes of up to {{convert|2100|m|ft|-2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Gorman>{{cite book|author=Gerard Gorman|title=Woodpeckers of the World: The Complete Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9LmnAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA181 |year=2014 |publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-1-4081-4717-7 |pages=181\u2013182}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nThe green-backed woodpecker feeds largely on ants and termites which it finds on trees. It often forages in pairs or may form part of small groups of mixed bird species.<ref name=Gorman/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* (Green-backed woodpecker = ) Little spotted woodpecker - [http://sabap2.adu.org.za/docs/sabap1/485.pdf Species text in The Atlas of Southern African Birds]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1264601}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:woodpecker, green-backed}}\n[[Category:Campethera|green-backed woodpecker]]\n[[Category:Birds of East Africa]]\n[[Category:Birds of Central Africa]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1849|green-backed woodpecker]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Wolffe713", "label": "safe", "comment": "Just a few punctuation corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green-backed_woodpecker"}
